<title>Medical Innovation Project Advisory Committee 
 -- PFF</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>

<H1>Medical Innovation Project Advisory Committee </H1>

<P>Hon. Louis Sullivan, M.D., returned to Morehouse School of Medicine in 1993 after
serving as Secretary of the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services in the
Bush Administration. He was the founding Dean and Director of the Medial
Education Program at Morehouse College, the first minority medical school founded
in the United States in this century. (404 -752-1892) 

<P>John E. Calfee, Ph.D., is a resident scholar at the American Enterprise
Institute. He has also served as a visiting senior fellow at the Brookings
Institution, an Associate Professor of Marketing at Boston University and an
Assistant Professor of Marketing at the College of Business, University of
Maryland. (202-862-5800)

<P>James Driscoll, Ph.D., serves as the vice president for policy at Direct Action
for Treatment Access, an activist organization for people with life threatening
diseases. An original founder of ACT-UP, he has spent the last 5 years lobbying
for FDA reform, for private sector incentives in drug research and a variety of
other treatment access and development issues. (415-552-0269)

<P>Robert Helms, Ph.D., is resident scholar and director of Health Policy Studies
Institute at the American Enterprise Institute. From 1981 to 1989, he served as
Assistant Secretary for Planning and Evaluation and as Deputy Assistant Secretary
for Health Policy at the Department of Health and Human Services. (202-862-5800)

<P>Peter Barton Hutt, Esq., is a well known food and drug lawyer at the Washington,
D.C., law firm of Covington & Burling. From 1971 to 1975, he served as Chief
Counsel for the Food and Drug Administration, where he was instrumental in
establishing the OTC drug review, the biological drugs review and in shaping the
drug efficacy study implementation (DESI) program for pre-1962 new drugs.
(202-662-6000)

<P>Sam Kazman, Esq., serves as general counsel of the Competitive Enterprise
Institute, a free market advocacy organization headquartered in Washington, D.C.
His writings include "Deadly Overcaution: FDA's Drug Approval Process" and "Death
by Regulation." (202-331-1010) 

<P>James Kitterman serves as executive director of the Candlelighters Childhood
Cancer Foundation. He has also served as director of marketing at The University
Club of Washington and public affairs director of the National Kidney Foundation
of the National Capital Area. (301-657-8401) 
Barbara Lawton, Ph.D., currently holds concurrent positions as Deming Professor
of Management at the University of Colorado, Boulder and as president of the W.
Edwards Deming Foundation. A senior fellow at The Progress & Freedom Foundation,
she is former director of Total Quality for Albany International and served as
advisory board member and lecturer at Fordham University. (303- 492-1591)

<P>Fred McChesney, Ph.D., J.D., currently serves as a Robert T. Thompson Professor
of Law and Business and Professor of Economics at the Emory University School of
Law. He has served as visiting professor at the University of Chicago Law School,
Universite d' Aix-Marseille (France), Oxford University, Centro di Formazione e
Studi (Italy), and Cornell University Law School. (404-727-6816)

<P>Henry I. Miller, M.D., is a Robert Wesson Fellow of Scientific Philosophy and
Public Policy at the Hoover Institution and a consulting professor at the
Institute for International Studies, Stanford University. He has served in
varying positions at the Food and Drug Administration and the National Institutes
of Health. (415-725-0185)

<P>Mr. Keith Mowry is the manager for accreditation and international affairs at
Underwriters Laboratories, an independent, not for profit product safety
certification organization. (708-272-8800) 

<P>Paul Rubin, Ph.D., is Professor of Economics at Emory University; adjunct fellow
at the Manhattan Institute; adjunct scholar at the American Enterprise and Cato
Institutes and The Georgia Public Policy Foundation; and Vice President of the
Southern Economics Association. He is editor-in-chief of Managerial and Decision
Economics. He served as Senior Economist on President Reagan's Council on
Economic Advisers. (404-727-6365) 

<P>Eugene Schonfeld, Ph.D., is president and co-founder of the National Kidney
Cancer Association. He is the founder of Schonfeld and Associates, a research
publishing company, and has 20 years of experience as an entrepreneur and
consultant to major corporations. (708-332-1051) 

<P>Frankie Trull serves as president of the Foundation of Biomedical Research and as
president for the National Association for Biomedical Research. She is also
president of Policy Directions, Inc. a government relations firm in Washington,
D.C., specializing in medical research and FDA issues. (202-457-0654)

<P>Gail R. Wilensky, Ph.D., is a senior fellow at Project HOPE, an international
health organization. She served in the Bush Administration as Deputy Assistant to
the President for Policy Development, and has also served as Administrator of the
Health Care Financing Administration in the Department of Health and Human
Services. (301-656-7401)<p>

<center>



</center>

