<head>
<title>Plan to Replace and Improve FDA Approval Process Unveiled -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>


<h1>Plan to Replace and Improve FDA Approval Process Unveiled</h1>

<b>For Immediate Release<br>
June 19, 1995<p>
Contact: Rick O'Donnell, (202) 484-2312</b></br>

<p>

The Progress & Freedom Foundation today introduced a plan to privatize many
functions of the Food and Drug Administration's drug and medical device approval
processes. The proposal would give experts at centers of medical excellence and
other private entities, licensed by the FDA, oversight of new products' movement
through the various stages of development.<p>

"This plan maintains our current high standards for safety and effectiveness, but
would expedite the process by which health-enhancing new products reach
patients," said Louis Sullivan, M.D., former Secretary of Health and Human
Services and chairman of the Foundation's Medical Innovation Project advisory
committee. "The experience of European countries has demonstrated that
non-government entities can play a very positive role in getting safe and
effective products to patients."<p>

The proposal, "The Future of Medical Innovation:  A New Approach for Bringing
Medical Products to Market," would separate oversight of the drug and device
approval process from the government's role in maintaining and enforcing legally
mandated safety and effectiveness standards. New private sector organizations,
certified by the FDA, would compete to offer a faster, lower-cost approval
process while ensuring that new medical products meet current standards.<p>

"Bureaucratic delays and political inertia have for too long prevented common
sense reform," said Jeffrey A. Eisenach, president of the Foundation.  "Every day
the current system stays in place is another day Americans die needless deaths
and suffer senseless pain.  It's time to replace the current system with one that
makes sense for the 1990s and the 21st Century."<p>

Crafted by The Progress & Freedom Foundation, a Washington, D.C.-based think
tank, the study was released for public comment and will be refined and expanded
in light of additional findings. The study was researched and produced by a
working group whose members include:<p>

<ul>

Thomas Lenard, Ph.D., Senior Fellow and Director Of Regulatory Studies at the
Foundation<p>

Ralph A. Epstein, M.D., Adjunct Fellow at the Foundation and Professor of
Anesthesiology, University of Connecticut<p>

Robert Tollison, Ph.D., Adjunct Fellow at the Foundation and Duncan Black
Professor of Economics, George Mason University<p>

W. Kip Viscusi, Ph.D., Adjunct Fellow at the Foundation and George G. Allen
Professor of Economics, Duke University<p>

William M. Wardell, M.D., Ph.D., Adjunct Fellow at the Foundation and President,
Protein Engineering Corporation and Wardell Associates International<p>

</ul>

"Many of our drug and medical device companies are able to offer products to
patients in Europe years before they ever receive FDA approval," said co-author 
Wardell.  "Not only does this cause needless suffering and death by denying
patients the benefits of effective medical technology, it hinders many of
America's major industries, thus slowing economic growth and job creation."<p>

The report proposes a new framework for bringing drugs and medical devices to
market, including:<p>

<ul>

<li>Decentralizing the product approval process to encourage innovation and reduce
costs and delays;<p>

<li>Making the approval process more predictable and less subject to bureaucratic
whim and delay; and,<p>

<li>Shifting the cost of the approval process from individual taxpayers to the
corporations that develop and market drugs.<p>

</ul>

"There is a widespread consensus on the part of industry, patient groups and
other observers of the FDA that substantial problems exist in the current system.
True reform requires a new institutional arrangement for bringing medical
products to market, not just tinkering around the edges," said Lenard.<p>

The Progress & Freedom Foundation is a non-partisan research and educational
organization dedicated to creating a positive vision of the future founded in the
historic principles of the American Idea, and to detailing the policies needed to
achieve that future.<p>
<center>
<a href="/pff/"><img border=0 width=234 height=32 src="multi/gif/pff-footer-home.gif" alt="Return to PFF Home Page"></a>
</center>
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
