<html><head><title>  A People's Budget -- PFF</title></head><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center> 
<h2>A People's Budget</h2>
<P>
By <a href="/pff/people/director.html#Eisenach">Jeffrey A. Eisenach</a></center><p>
<P>




	Congress is in trouble again.  Recent polls show people are less and less satisfied with its performance.  Indeed, according to a recent survey, only 35 percent of Americans approve of the way Congress is doing its job.
<p>
	Liberals would have us believe the problem stems from Republican efforts to "go too far" or "cut too much."  As ABC anchorman Peter Jennings put it, they believe the November election was nothing more than a  "temper tantrum."  People didn't really know what they were doing on November 8, the theory goes, and the more they now read about "draconian" cuts, the more they come to realize that balancing the budget, cutting Federal spending and -- worst of all -- getting some of their money back in the form of tax cuts, was just a childish fantasy.
<p>
	But a closer look at voter's attitudes leaves no doubt it's liberals who are fantasizing.   Many Americans who are dissatisfied with Congress say they want more cut from federal spending, not less.  Republicans may be in trouble, but if so it's because they are moving too slowly, cutting too little, compromising too much.  Republican Members went back to their districts for the August recess expecting to hear angry constituents complaining about program cuts.  Instead, they were told to keep at it; even on the contentious issue of Medicare, Members found most voters agreeing that the system needs major reform before it bankrupts the government.
<p>
	Managing their new majority is no picnic for the Republican leadership.  True, a majority of House Republicans are freshmen and sophomores, most of whom understand voters' want dramatic change.  But  four out of ten Republican Congressmen have been in Congress for six years or more, long enough to have a big stake in the status quo.  And while House Speaker Newt Gingrich wisely appointed a number of younger members to chair important committees and subcommittees, 57 of the 101 chairmen have been in Congress for ten years or more.
<p>
	And then there's the Senate, where the average age among Republicans is 58, and the average Congressional tenure (counting time in the House for those who served there first) is 10.2 years.  Virtually all of the leading Senate "moderates" are also old bulls -- Senators Cohen, Chafee, Jeffords and Hatfield have, between them,  served in Congress for 95 years!
<p>
	In <i>The People's Budget</I>, a recently released book I co-authored with former Perot pollster Frank Luntz and three others, we started out by asking what kind of Federal government Americans thought they were getting when they voted to end 40 years of Democratic rule. The answer:  They wanted to shrink the government in Washington by at least 25 percent, and most wanted it cut by fully one-third.
<p>
	Importantly, people were not necessarily anti-government -- just anti-Washington.  They wanted power sent back to them:  To the people, to local governments, and to the states.
<p>
	With that in mind, we designed a complete budget of the U.S. government, a budget that shrinks Federal spending as a proportion of the gross domestic product from its current level of more than 21 percent down to 15.7 percent, precisely the one-third cut most people said they wanted.  We do it by getting the Federal government completely out of areas where most people don't think it belongs (education, welfare, roads and sewers, etc.), by getting serious about cutting corporate welfare and other special interest spending, and by moving quickly to replace the obsolete Medicare program with a market-oriented system that will guarantee better care for the elderly at a much lower cost.
<p>
	All of this is possible with no smoke and mirrors.  We used the same conservative economic assumptions applied by the Congressional Budget Office, and didn't even count the savings in interest on the debt that would result from balancing the budget over seven years.
<p>
	By shrinking Washington's budget, our proposal would increase the family budget -- eliminating most Federal excise taxes (e.g. on gasoline, telephones and tobacco) and cutting income taxes 22 percent beyond what Republicans are now proposing.
<p>
	Most members of the Republican leadership support this kind of serious downsizing.  Speaker Gingrich has called our plan "a blue-print for replacing the welfare state," and Budget Committee Chairman Kasich even wrote the foreword for the book.  On the Democratic side, some members, like Mississippi Congressman Mike Parker, are to the right of many Republicans in supporting real change.  There just aren't enough of them.
<p>
	All the data suggests the voters are still where they were on November 8, looking for a Congress that will pass a "people's budget" that dramatically shrinks the government in Washington.  But the evidence is mounting that it's going to take one more election -- now barely a year away -- to reinforce the revolutionary troops voters sent to Congress last November.
<p>
<i>Jeffrey A. Eisenach is President of The Progress & Freedom Foundation and co-author (with Edwin Dale, Frank Luntz, Timothy Muris and William Schneider) of </i>The People's Budget<i> (Regnery, 1995), which is available at bookstores nation-wide or by calling 1-800-955-5493.</I>
<P>
<center></center>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></html>





