<html><head><title>  A Budget for the People -- PFF</title></head><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center> 
<h2>A Budget for the People</h2>
<P>
By <a href="/pff/people/afellow.html#Luntz">Frank Luntz</a></center><p>
<P>

	Public opinion research -- polling -- is one of the critical devices by which the political class comes to know the hopes and dreams, the fears and concerns of the electorate. Although much maligned, it is, as Ben Wattenberg noted, one of America's three unique contributions to the practice of democracy.

<p>	As Congress begins the daunting task of balancing the Federal budget, what are the American people saying about the budget in dozens of national surveys and dozens of focus groups in all regions of the country?  They offer a single, definitive conclusion:  The American people consider the dramatic reduction and restructuring of the government in Washington to be far more than a fiscal necessity; they consider it a moral imperative.
<p>
	The imperative is to cut spending, not balance the budget. This is an important distinction.  The budget deficit is, to be sure, a symptom of Washington's lack of fiscal discipline. But most Americans do not regard eliminating the deficit per se to be an urgent priority.
<p>
	When people seek to explain why American society seems to be crumbling about them, they point fingers at Washington.  The Federal budget is not merely wasteful -- the public estimates that about 50 cents of every dollar goes up in smoke -- it is often injurious to the health of our nation.
<p>
	The electorate takes a collective look around and sees what 30 years of bloated budgets in Washington has built -- high rise ghettos, consigning the poor to live in cesspools of crime and drugs -- and it thinks, "not with my tax dollars you don't."  They see Washington subsidizing illegitimacy in the inner city and vile artistic contempt for religion in the comfortable suburbs, and they say, "this is wrong."
<p>
	Eighty percent of the American public thinks that declining individual morality and the breakup of the family presage a crisis that will be the dominant political issue into the new millennium.  What voters want is for the government in Washington to stop spending money that is destructive to American civilization.
<p>
	When we ask the public what they are looking for from Washington, they emphasize four key elements:  accountability, responsibility, simplicity, and common sense.
<p>
<UL><LI>Accountability to hold their politicians answerable for what they say and what they do. Accountability to hold the programs liable for what is promised.
<P>
<li>Responsibility, that involves sending programs back home because you can hold your Representatives more beholden when you can touch them and feel them, which you can do in local government but you can't do in Washington.
<P>
<LI>Simplicity, that involves everything from the tax structure to all the various programs that do the same thing over and over and over again in a bureaucratic maze.
<P>
<li>Common sense, to recognize that programs delivered into the South Bronx will not be the same type of programs that you would deliver in South Dakota. They want each line in the budget to pass this simple test:  Does it move us toward or away from a healthy society of high moral character -- would I impose it on my family and neighborhood?
</ul><p>
	These are the four elements voters want to see in the Federal budget currently being written in the House and Senate.  They are less interested in how much needs to be cut to balance the budget than they are that the government stop spending money on things it cannot do well.
<p>
	The new majority in Congress should craft a budget that the American people, and not Washington policy wonks and lobbyists, want. That is why I co-authored a new book, <i>The People's Budget: A Common Sense Plan for Shrinking the Government in Washington</i>, which we believe is the budget the American people would write for the federal government.
<p>
	Among the main features of this people's budget:
<p>
	The responsibility for designing, running and paying for state and local programs should be returned to the states and localities, where it belongs -- and where people can hold elected officials more accountable for producing results.
<p>
	This would allow the government in Washington to be nearly one-third smaller, as a percentage of GDP, than it is today -- down from 22 percent to around 15 percent of GDP.
<p>
	Taxes would be reduced, giving people the funds to take care of themselves and their families, and giving states and localities the tax base they would need to take on their new responsibilities.
<p>
	Medicare would begin the transformation from a 1960s "command and control" bureaucracy to a 1990s system of consumer choice.
<p>
	The Federal budget would be balanced, and the debt would begin to shrink rapidly relative to the size of the economy.  With Medicare saved from bankruptcy and the budget deficit finally eliminated, the foundation would have been created to deal with the looming crisis in Social Security.
<p>
	Although many pollsters like to discuss their methodologies with reverent and obscure scientific-sounding terms, what we do is not rocket science -- indeed it is much more an art than any kind of science. There is no great mystery to what the American people want from their political leaders at this junction in our history.  They want hope, and they hope that we can arrest the decline of our society's character by arresting and then reversing the growth in our government.

<p>
<i>Frank Luntz, a pollster, is an adjunct fellow at The Progress & Freedom Foundation.  He did the polling for the 1994 Contract with America and the 1992 Perot Presidential Campaign.</I>
<br><P>
<center></center>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></html>
