<head>
<title>Buckley: Oh No! Running for President? -- 2/16/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
New York, February 16, 1996
</i>

<h2>
Oh No! Running for President?
</h2>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/
buckley
.html">
William F. Buckley Jr.
</a>

<P>
Mr. Yeltsin has announced that he will run for re-election as 
President of Russia. It is his duty to "consolidate all healthy forces 
and prevent shocks that could lead to a civil war." That is quite a 
threat to toss about, something no candidate in New Hampshire has got 
around to. In the past few months Mr. Yeltsin has got rid of those of 
his lieutenants identified with the reform movement. This greatly 
surprised those members of our State Department who rued the long 
interval back in 1991 during which Gorbachev was falling apart and 
U.S. policy refused to recognize the importance of Yeltsin. We did so 
only after that dramatic day in Red Square when Yeltsin defied the 
revolutionists and soon after was elected president.
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
It was demoralizing to read the assessment of Yeltsin by Vyacheslav 
Kostikov, Yeltsin's former press secretary. "Power is his ideology," 
he said, "his concubine if you want, his lover -- and his passion. 
Everything that is beyond the fight for power concerns him much less." 
When that remark about Yeltsin was aired, Kostikov was instantly fired 
(he had been ambassador to the Vatican). Fifty years earlier he'd have 
been instantly executed. Even ten years ago he would have suffered 
something more resonant than dismissal from a diplomatic post.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
There are many contenders for the presidency of Russia, but the 
thinking in some quarters is that there will be a run-off between the 
two lead candidates, and that they will be Yeltsin and Gennadi 
Zyuganov. Now Mr. Zyuganov, formerly a provincial teacher, is running 
on the Communist Party ticket and is thought the probable victor.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
It staggers the mind. Suppose that in Germany a politician were to run 
on the National Socialist Party ticket. He might say, "Let's see if 
this time around we can do it without killing the Jews, or invading 
France." Zyuganov being a very acute politician, it can't be said of 
him that he got tripped up into running as a Communist. As with 
Yeltsin, one can't know what this politician's internal designs or 
attachments or loyalties are. But Zyuganov proclaims his attachment to 
Communism, intending to persuade the Russians that much of the pain 
they now experience -- en route to a free society and a free market -- 
they didn't experience back then under Stalin and Brezhnev, when no 
one was ever fired from his job, prices were stable, and crime was at 
low tide. In December's parliamentary race Zyuganov faced a liberal 
challenger. At one of their encounters, posters were flaunted: 
"50,000,000 VICTIMS OF CIVIL WAR, COLLECTIVIZATION AND REPRESSION 
WOULD NOT VOTE FOR ZYUGANOV." He won handily.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The great revisionism is underway. It begins by closing the memory. 
Four years ago, 84 per cent of high-school students tested knew what 
the Gulag was. Today, only 34 per cent can tell you that the Gulag was 
that great charnel, the archipelago in which twenty million Russians 
were killed, either by execution squads, or starvation, or exposure. 
Such historical tablelands, when brought to the attention of the 
Communist candidate for President, are shrugged off as incidents of 
yesteryear. "We can't answer for the mistakes of the past."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
What is lost sight of is the primary finding of history in the matter 
of the Communist approach to government. It is that the cruelty, the 
repression, the economic sclerosis are an organic part of the whole. 
When Gorbachev authorized glasnost his critics proved absolutely 
correct, that glasnost would need to be repealed, or else that it 
would bring on the dissolution of the Communist enterprise, because 
free speech and Communism are irreconcilable. Yeltsin is already 
moving toward economic interventionism, and in his pursuit of power 
will almost certainly go further. The Communists in China are 
experimenting with economic freedom carefully sequestered, but their 
fear of its leverage on civil rights brings them to furious 
exhibitions of power and threat; because experience teaches that 
economic freedom requires a measure of personal freedom. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
So, after all of this, the next President of Russia might be a 
Communist. What will be his attitude toward the liberated republics? 
We know what the position is of Zhirinovsky, the hero of the super 
nationalists: bring them all back. If that were accomplished, we would 
be facing a Communist leader of a new Soviet Union and wondering, 
quite reasonably, whether it would be thought new for so very long.

<P><P>

<P>
<center>
[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/"> Columnists </a>]

<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/"> National Review </a> ]

<br>

</blockquote></blockquote>




