<html>
<head>
<title>Presidential Patter</title>
</head>
<center>
<h2>Presidential Patter</h2>
</center>
<hr>
New York, July 11 
<p>
<p>
There were about twenty people -- mostly men, four women -- engaged
in myriad activities, including law, banking, journalism, the academy.  
They have in common a bond to the conservative political enterprise  
which, to a not inconsiderable degree, is affected by their resolutions.  
And the evening's extemporaneous subject matter was the presidential  
race. 
<p> 
The rubric called for direct speech, freed of any obligation to diplomatic  
protocol. In that spirit, one commentator confessed his sense of security  
with Senator Dole. "I feel comfortable with opportunists, because I  
always know what to expect." Dole, most agreed, is scheduled to be  
nominated, the beneficiary of a Republican tradition that consummates  
the nomination of the front-runner. 
<p>
Bush led in 1988 and of course in 1992, and was confirmed by the  
Republican Convention. Reagan led in 1980, Ford in 1976, Goldwater in  
1964. By contrast, the Democrats make way for relatively obscure  
candidates. The polls reported that 2 per cent of the American people  
knew, in January 1972, the name of George McGovern: six months later  
he was nominated for President. The polls in January 1976 recorded 3  
per cent of the public knew the name of Jimmy Carter, and 12 months  
later he was inaugurated President of the United States. 
<p>
Such arrivals of the star in the third act tend not to happen in the GOP.  
Accordingly, Mr. Dole would need to slip up, something in which he is  
practiced, but not something he has done in the past few months, during  
which his campaign has revealed near-perfect professional performance.  
Another commentator opined that Dole might well suffer during the  
campaign, when his age might become visible. FDR was able to  
campaign in 1944 as if whole in mind and body, but this is not so easily  
done any more with the ubiquitous television cameras. And even without  
a slip, there will be some heavy breathing in the voting booths at the  
prospect of sending to the White House a man who would be 73 when  
inaugurated, 77 at the turn of the century. 
<p>
A participant took the floor to pass along something he situated at least  
half way between rumor and fact. He had been told (needless to say, by a  
reliable source) that Colin Powell would figure heavily in the politics of  
1996. 
<p> 
Just to begin with, whoever gets the presidential nod, Powell is almost  
certain to be invited to run for Vice President. If indeed Mr. Dole gets  
the nomination, Powell will feel a very strong impulse to serve him as  
Vice President, on the grounds that it is all but inconceivable that Bob  
Dole would run for a second term. In other words, Colin Powell would  
be inaugurated as President in January of 2001. 
<p>
Now on this subject, the commentator went on, his word has it that  
Powell will, as scheduled, proceed to do his book tour during September  
and October. But at the end of the tour, he will make a declaration of  
principles addressed unambiguously to the political scene -- and that set  
of political principles will be unambiguously conservative. That act will  
immediately make him a presidential candidate unless he rules himself  
out, intending to accept the Vice Presidency with Dole. We need to  
remember about General Powell -- or to teach ourselves, if we did not  
know it -- that he is the most spellbinding political orator since Reagan.  
"No one else comes even close to his amalgam of dignity, self- 
deprecation, firmness, and hope.'' 
<p> 
Still, whoever it is will need to contend with Bill Clinton. An observer  
began by reciting the disqualifications of the incumbent. "Just to begin  
with, he seems to have repealed the public bias against adultery." On  
every important position he has taken conflicting stands. He is scorned  
by the rest of the world, manipulated by his own staff, arrested in his  
thinking by any visiting shaman. "Still . . . He has the powers of  
Houdini. Throw him in the trunk of the car with eight chains bound  
around him, toss the car into the ocean, and before you know it, he  
comes bobbing up to the surface.'' 
 <p>
Even now, the observer continued, Clinton is substantially up over his  
ratings of a few months ago, and it is by no means certain that he will be  
swamped by the Republican nominee. Anything can happen, which is  
bad news for the Republic, and there is no insurance policy written to  
cope with this contingency.
<p>

</DOC>
