<head>
<title>MURDER DOWN</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>MURDER DOWN?</h2>
</center>
<hr>
 New York, July 18 
<p>
<p>
The headline was wonderfully reassuring to this part of the world.  
"Murder Rate Plunges in New York City." There are corollary decreases  
in other crime -- robberies down 22 per cent, auto theft down 25 per  
cent. The question arises: Is this a statistical blip? If not -- if it is a  
genuine trend downward -- what are its causes? More jails? Less crack  
cocaine? A dulling of the criminal spirit? 
<p>
The optimists should read the essay in the July Atlantic Monthly by  
Adam Walinsky. For that matter, so should the pessimists. It is an  
eloquent and heavily informed overview of what has happened in the  
past three decades, and Mr. Walinsky wonders why America permitted it  
to happen. Everyone deplores the high rate of crime but there is nothing  
resembling a true mobilization to combat it. 
<p>
Here are the salient figures. In the 1960s, for every violent crime  
committed we had 3.3 police officers. In 1993, for every police officer  
there were 3.4 violent crimes. Consider New Haven, Connecticut. In  
1990, with its population down 14 per cent from 1960, its robberies had  
increased more than 100 times, or 10,000 per cent. In this perspective,  
the reduction of crime in New York is, however welcome, a mere fillip.  
And the figures on police stretch out to less than one-tenth the effective  
police power of thirty years ago. ". . . in another formulation, each police  
officer today must deal with 11.45 times as many violent crimes as his  
predecessor of years gone by." 
 <p>
We have a half-million police officers, and the proposal in the crime bill  
of Mr. Clinton was an extra one hundred thousand. How many  
policemen would we need to add in order to restore the same balance as  
in 1960 of police to violent crimes? Five million. 
<p>
Are we making any strides in that direction? Only in the private sector.  
One and one-half million security officers protect corporations, private  
residential areas, shopping malls. Good. But a lot of people spend their  
time outside privately protected areas, like the overwhelming majority of  
the American people. The Department of Justice estimates that 83 per  
cent of all Americans will be victims of violent crime at least once in  
their lives; about a quarter, victims of three or more violent crimes. 
<p>
Two out of five killers, Mr. Walinsky advises us, are undetected. These  
missing killers commit what the trade calls "stranger murders." The  
notion that crime is overwhelmingly a matter of passion is simply no  
longer arguable. And the chances of the stranger murderer getting away  
are 80 per cent. Walinsky quotes a New York Times description of Omar  
Rosario going to work in a grocery store, whose previous owner was  
murdered. "Rosario prepares for work by donning a bulletproof vest and  
sliding a 9-millimeter semi-automatic into his waistband. When a young  
man with one arm hidden inside his coat enters the store, Mr. Rosario  
takes out his pistol and eases it halfway into the pocket of his pants, his  
finger on the trigger. He faces the man and lets him see the gun in his  
hand. He wants to make it clear that if the young man pulls a gun, he  
will be killed.''' 
<p> 
That's one way to go, but it hasn't had a large effect. In the last ten years,  
twice as many Americans were killed by strangers as were on the  
battlefield during the ten years we fought in Vietnam. In the black  
community the statistics are dire: One out of every 21 black men is  
killed, double the rate of American servicemen in the Second World  
War. "The collapse of the black lower class is a creation not of history  
but of this generation. It has been a deliberate if misguided act of  
government to create a welfare system that began the destruction of black  
family life. It was the dominant culture that desanctified morality,  
celebrated license, and glorified fecklessness." 
<p> 
Adam Walinsky has for many years advocated a Police Corps, an ROTC  
that would offer four-year college scholarships to young people in return  
for four years of police service following their graduation. This is not an  
expenditure from which the Contract crowd should shrink. To begin  
with, it is to confirm the most solemn obligation of government, which is  
to provide for domestic security. "President Clinton has requested $261.4  
billion for defense against foreign enemies who killed fewer than a  
hundred Americans in all of last year. It would be silly to suggest that  
the Federal Government should not or cannot spend an eighth as much --  
2 per cent of even a shrunken federal budget -- to defend the nation  
against domestic enemies who killed more than 10,000 people who were  
strangers to them in 1994, and who will surely kill more in every year  
that lies ahead."
<p>
</DOC>
