<html>
<head>
<title>Why Not ID?</title>
</head><center>
<h2>Why Not ID?</h2></center>
<p>
<p>
<hr>
 NEW YORK, JULY 25
<p>
Thirty years ago the philosopher/strategist James Burnham included a 
chapter in his book Suicide of the West in which he undertook to list 
the stands in public policy that distinguish the American conservative 
from the American liberal. For instance? Capital punishment: most 
conservatives are in favor of it, most liberals against. Gun control, 
the other way around. Many of the dividing points had to do with 
aspects of foreign policy during the Cold War, no longer relevant. If 
Mr. Burnham were alive and writing today no doubt he'd have included 
in his list strategic anti-missile defense. There is a Grand Canyon 
that divides conservative and liberal opinion on that subject.
<p>
We paleos (for "paleolithic conservatives": i.e., those of us who were 
conservative beginning way back in past geological eras) were weaned 
in a kind of anti-cyber, anti-computer tradition. Mr. Burnham listened 
with instinctive approval to a classmate who initiated the idea of a 
chain-letter from one friend to two friends to four friends to sixteen 
friends urging a quiet mutiny against numerical identification. The 
idea was always to misplace one digit in anything that requires 
absolutely accurate disclosure. A kind of quiet sabotage of the 
computer age, was the dream. If enough people wrote 123465 where 
123456 was the correct code, then the mighty house of Mainframe would 
come tumbling down.
<p>
It is in fidelity to that tradition that so many conservatives oppose 
any move toward an identification number. Professor Thomas Sowell of 
the Hoover Institution has written that "nothing polarizes the 
political Left and Right like the idea of a national identity card." 
The Nazis and the Communists and indeed the South Africans required an 
ID. Isn't that reason enough for free governments to shrink at the 
thought of it?
<p>
Not in my view. In the past three weeks I have three times been asked 
to give my Social Security number. Why? Presumably because no two 
people have the same Social Security number. When we were in the army 
and desired to get free postage, we were required to write our serial 
number on the envelope. When we travel abroad we are required to hand 
over our passports, each one individually numbered. In many situations 
the requirement is to show your driver's license, preferably in states 
in which your picture also appears on that license.
<p>
What then is the reason for such heated opposition to an 
identification number, as has been proposed by various congressmen 
anxious to do something about illegal immigration? The idea, as we 
understand it, is to develop an ID which can't be violated by the 
owner or duplicated by a black marketeer. Presumably what then happens 
is that the young man who asks for a job in a restaurant or at a 
construction firm is asked (under obligation of law) to show his ID. 
If he can't come up with it, he is deemed to be illegal, and doesn't 
get hired.
<p>
What's wrong with that? "Control is the name of the game for 
liberals," Professor Sowell writes, "even when they call it 
'compassion.' A national identity card would not only permit even 
greater government snooping into people's private lives, the 
information gathered would almost inevitably lead to more laws forcing 
more people to do more things the way the politicians want them done. 
It is a down payment on totalitarianism." Mr. Sowell sees a tunnel 
ahead, and the light at the end of it is the complete submission by 
the individual to the government.
<p>
We should concede this, namely that in totalitarian societies an ID is 
absolutely essential. The contrapositive, however, is not justified -- 
that every society that has an ID will become a totalitarian society. 
As noted, already there is an ID of sorts, done by Social Security. As 
a weapon against illegal immigration it is not reliable because it is 
very easy to get a Social Security card. But if a) it is a legitimate 
goal to regulate immigration, then b) the means to do this effectively 
should be there, and c) it would not appear to make sense to deny the 
government instruments that are not inherently cruel or indecent. To 
authorize an ID that merely proves you are who you say you are is not 
the same thing as to authorize a government enema or truth serum.
<p>
On such matters one thinks of George Gilder, the American conservative 
bard of the computer, whose threnodies remind us how much we owe to 
the computer, not least that it enables us, without further ado, to 
establish that we are Americans, entitled to the rights guaranteed us 
under the Constitution. 
<p>
</DOC>
