<html>
<head>
<title>The Susan Smith Case</title>
</head>
<center><h2>The Susan Smith Case</h2></center>
<p>
<p>
<hr>
NEW YORK, JULY 28
<p>
<p>
The brother of Susan Smith asked the jurors what would be the point of 
sentencing Mrs. Smith to death -- hasn't there been enough tragedy in 
her family already? That statement did not resonate very widely 
because Mrs. Smith's family comprised the two boys she murdered, and 
an ex-husband who had already told the jury he thought she should be 
executed. And of course the point logically arises: If there is a law 
in South Carolina specifying execution for capital offenses, what 
capital offenses are we going to sub-specify as especially appropriate 
for execution?
<p>
Well of course no one disputes the sheer horror of the means by which 
Mrs. Smith elected to kill her children. Under the circumstances, the 
defense needed to go in a different direction from what the defense 
has done with O. J. Simpson. It needed to plead with the jury the 
awful aspects of her own life.
<p>
Newspaper readers are familiar with the details: the suicide of her 
father when she was 6, seduction by her stepfather when she entered 
her teens, a marriage that resulted in two sons followed by a divorce 
followed by a love affair with her boss alongside a love affair with 
her boss's son coextensive with sex with her stepfather. The reason 
for all of this, the defense explained, is the trauma of the suicide 
of her father and the fear she felt that to break away from her 
stepfather would be in the nature of renewing the wound that had left 
her fatherless at 6 -- and how are we doing, ladies and gentlemen of 
the jury, have we got you in the Menendez mood? You do remember the 
Menendez brothers, and how convincing it was that they really felt 
they had to empty their shotguns at their mother and father?
<p>
It pays, if only as an exercise, to credit the teleology of Susan 
Smith's mental development. Let us assume that the suicide of her 
father led her compulsively to submit to sex with her stepfather. Let 
us suppose that that driving compulsion to love copiously led her to 
leave her husband and take to her bed her boss, and then his son; that 
her anxiety for the continued sexual devotion of the son led her to 
interpret his statement that he would not marry a woman and take on 
the burden of two children to the perfectly logical conclusion that 
the children were an insufferable burden: that that led her 
compulsively to strap the two impediments onto the back seat of the 
car, and let it slide into the lake. A quite natural sense of self-
protection caused her to tell police of a black abductor who at 
gunpoint had whisked the children away. And then after nine days, as 
the circumstantial evidence tightened about her, she began to descry a 
noose. At that point she confessed.
<p>
Now the refinement of the McNaghten defense, which requires the 
prosecution to establish that the defendant knew the difference 
between right and wrong, would not appear to have applied. Mrs. Smith 
acknowledged to her ex-husband that she was "sorry" she hadn't 
accepted his offer to take the boys home with him.
<p>
What was fought over, in the jury deliberations, is really the 
question of capital punishment. 1) The gravity of the offense was 
established. 2) The defendant's knowledge that what she did was wrong 
wasn't doubted. In which case, 3) shouldn't she be sentenced to death?
<p>
The risk in capital prosecutions was of course highlighted by the 
Menendez verdict. The law, roundly stated, tells us that you may not 
kill another person except in self-defense. The Menendez brothers had 
no such excuse, but they were got off by a lawyer who mesmerized the 
jury into rogue theories of psychological compulsions.
<p>
Such arguments go to eristic legal lengths. Suppose we begin with the 
simple postulate that murder is aberrational behavior. Then the 
question -- under the handling of defense lawyers -- becomes: What 
caused such behavior? Mean parents? Suicidal fathers? Cruelty? Sex? 
Fear? -- the list is infinite because the postulate is fixed. It is 
that if somebody is murdered, it has to be that the murderer departed 
from the moral fixes that restrain other human beings. Accordingly the 
quest is for the cause of the misbehavior, and the only penological 
reason to keep the murderer in jail is to prevent him from doing it 
again.
<p>
It became, really, that all over again, a fight over capital 
punishment. "What happened to Michael and Alex is a tragedy," said the 
defense. "To strap Susan in a chair and send 2,000 volts into her in 
the name of justice -- "
<p>
He was interrupted by the prosecution, who reminded him that more 
humane means of execution had been authorized by the State of South 
Carolina. But the State of South Carolina might just as well abolish 
capital punishment now that Susan Smith has been spared.
<p>
<p>
</DOC>
