<html>
<head>
<title>Hiroshima -- Happy Birthday?</title>
</head>
<center><h2>Hiroshima -- Happy Birthday?</center></h2>
<p>
<p>
<hr>
William F. Buckley Jr, New York August 4th
<p>
Harry Truman was not an ambiguist, just to begin with. And in any 
case, important declarations are usually summary. "I do," is all that 
is necessary in answer to the question, "Do you take this man for your 
lawfully wedded husband?" When asked for final approval to drop the 
atomic bomb over Hiroshima, Harry Truman, in Potsdam, scribbled out in 
longhand, "Suggestion approved. Release when ready." It seems a 
millennium since the idiomatically similar order was given by Admiral 
Dewey to the captain of his flagship at the Battle of Manila Bay in 
1898: "You may fire when you are ready, Gridley." Truman authorized 
the non-platonic beginning of the nuclear age, at the convenience of 
the commander of a bomber squadron on the 39-square-mile island of 
Tinian.
<p>
Time magazine did a good job last week in describing the elements of 
the contest between East and West that was finally detonated at Pearl 
Harbor, and a harrowing account of the terrible bloodiness of the 
Pacific war and of the breathless interval between the bomb's falling 
at Nagasaki and the quiet-spoken words of the Emperor Hirohito, 
besought by a cabinet divided between surrender and suicide. He 
elected to surrender.
<p>
Books have been written and prayers for divine guidance said to 
examine the morality of the bomb. If it is true that the intentions of 
the perpetrator are the final determinants of moral rectitude, then 
Truman is clearly blameless. He had weighed reports of projected 
American casualties in an invasion of Japan; estimates ranged between 
thirty thousand and a half-million dead and wounded. The same 
strategists projected Japanese casualties at many times that number, 
and even as Truman thought about the question -- before even the trial 
bomb at Alamogordo had established that Little Boy (Hiroshima) and Fat 
Man (Nagasaki) would indeed work their devastation -- we were 
routinely proceeding with our concentrated bombing of Japanese cities. 
Over eighty thousand were killed in the firebombings of Tokyo even as, 
a few months earlier, we had in three waves killed almost as many 
Germans in Dresden with the saturation bombings.
<p>
Did Harry Truman give sufficient thought to alternatives? There was 
the possibility of encouraging an earlier intervention against Japan 
by the Soviet army. There was the possibility of amending the terms of 
surrender sharply enough to affect the thinking of the bitter-enders 
in the Japanese military. The answer to these questions can't be 
given, not because the alternatives weren't presented to Truman, but 
because we don't know to what extent they captured his attention. We 
had only just conquered Okinawa, with a loss of 12,500 American 
servicemen. A national poll showed 90 per cent of Americans supporting 
in effect unconditional surrender. As far as Truman was concerned, we 
should give him the benefit of the doubt: the nuclear bomb was simply 
the next weapon in line. We had traveled, in Truman's lifetime, from 
biplanes to B-29s. Why cavil at a single bomb that could effect the 
same damage as a thousand bombers?
<p>
The soul-searching came later. It required centuries to mobilize 
civilized opinion against slavery and against torture. It is not 
finally settled even now on capital punishment. Nor is it on nuclear 
weaponry as a deterrent, but then of course in order to deter, nuclear 
weapons need to threaten. A civilized scholar very close to several 
Presidents once observed to me that if the Soviet nuclear flotilla had 
actually launched, he would have seen no purpose in counselling the 
President to launch our own: what had been there as a deterrent, 
designed to be conclusive, hadn't worked -- so why kill 150 million 
Russians? No one of course will ever know whether such reasoning would 
have stayed the hand of a U.S. President. It sufficed that Soviet 
leaders did not rule out nuclear retaliation: whereupon nuclear 
stalemate was born. It had a long life.
<p>
It does surprise that the evangelistic energy now spent on the horrors 
of Hiroshima does not bear little buds that would encourage the 
development of defensive means to intercept the hypothetical nuclear 
bomb of tomorrow. For reasons quite impossible to understand, those 
most transfixed by the horrors of Hiroshima are most unconcerned by, 
or even hostile to, any effort to accost not the evil in men's minds 
and nature -- perhaps because this is not possible -- but the weapons 
such men can deploy.
<p>
</DOC>
