<html><head><title>Buckley:  What Made Colin Run?</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<center>

<i>NEW YORK, NOVEMBER 10</i>

<hr>

<h2>What Made Colin Run?</h2><br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/buckley.html"><b><i>William F. Buckley Jr.</i></b></a><hr><br></center>

The grave dignity of Colin Powell's announcement had the effect of 
causing dismayed observers to thrash out at those who had opposed his 
candidacy. This is a psychological phenomenon: Mom has an accident 
coming home from work and reproaches abound -- Why did Dad let her go 
on working so late in life? Why didn't Sonny, who after all is a car 
salesman, force Mom to get a better, stronger car? To say nothing of 
Mom's stupid eye doctor, who should have known Mom's glasses needed 
strengthening.
<p>
It happens even to wise and street-smart chappies, e.g., William 
Safire of the New York Times. He let himself go twice in his Powell 
column, once directly, once obliquely. He set up his target by 
carefully orienting his argument as testimony to General Powell's 
courage, a technique he knows as paralepsis, which is the affirmation 
of the point you wish to make by denying it ("I come to bury Caesar, 
not to praise him"); only Safire did it the other way around. 
"Certainly Powell was not chased off the field by the performance last 
week before the National Press Club of the Hard-Right Follies; the 
finger-wagging by that old abortion-and-school-prayer set was manna 
from Heaven for a moderate Republican's nomination campaign." Later in 
the same column, Mr. Safire made reference to "Arlen Specter, the pro-
choice candidate, with nobody on his side on that issue except the 
majority of Republican voters."
<p>
The Miami Herald weighed in weightily. "True conservatives want frugal 
government, but also prudent investments in children, concern for the 
needy, and a desire to widen economic opportunity, not just pile 
benefits onto the wealthy. General Powell says that 'the party of 
Lincoln' (a phrase borrowed from Kemp) [my impression was that the 
phrase was first used by Andrew Johnson] can balance these interests 
best, and that's why he chose to be a Republican. But he recognizes 
that he will have to fight -- hard -- to restore those values to a 
party lately hijacked by the Christian Coalition and its acolytes." 
And then Maureen Dowd, also of the New York Times, contributed the 
news that General Powell "had exposed the Christian Right as a 
panicked sectarian phenomenon."
<p>
What are we to make of all this? The Christian Right is indeed 
sectarian, which is why it isn't the Muslim Right, or the Jewish 
Right, however much the three faiths may have in common. And 
"panicked" is probably a defensible term to describe a movement deeply 
concerned by a rise of 400 per cent in serious crimes during the past 
generation and 300 per cent in illegitimate births. The word 
"panicked" is subjectively used, of course. Only three days ago, one 
newspaper report informed us that President Clinton was "panicked" at 
the prospect of General Powell's running. We have to assume that a 
metaphor was intended, given that nobody caught Bill Clinton about to 
throw himself out the window.
<p>
But the reference by Bill Safire is confusing, the business about 
"that old abortion-and-school-prayer set." Either he is saying that 
there should be term limits on concern over abortion and school 
prayer, or else he is saying that the questions have been debated and 
are behind us. It isn't that Mr. Safire is indisposed to stay in a 
battle for as long as it takes. He was a doughty soldier during the 
Cold War, which began many years before Roe v. Wade, but Safire was in 
there right up until the Berlin Wall came down, God bless him, and if 
it takes a hundred years to guarantee the safety of Israel, we cannot 
reasonably doubt that Bill Safire's great-grandchildren will be 
sounding the Zionist bell, and more power to them. If he is saying 
that, on the contrary, people ought to give up on school prayer, there 
are those who respectfully disagree, among them -- who knows? -- God!, 
who is contingently capable of influencing elections. And a call to 
acknowledge human life in the fetus isn't a question of the kind one 
ought to get bored about unless research absolutely establishes that, 
all the time, a fetus was really no different from a tomato.
<p>
The right-wing gentlemen who met last week to serve notice on General 
Powell that he had made references disquieting to them, honorable 
representatives of conservative positions within the GOP, spoke 
respectably on the issues to which they have devoted themselves for 
many years. They didn't raise a single question about General Powell 
that hadn't been raised, that same week, by George Will, but Mr. 
Safire and Miss Dowd and the Miami Herald have an instinctive sense -- 
maybe it was sharpened by reading General Powell's autobiography? -- 
who to pick on when Mom has an accident on the highway, and who to let 
alone.<p>

<br><center>

[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi"> Columnists </a>]

<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/welcome.html"> National Review </a>]

