HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 07:22:01 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 03-Jun-96 20:59:50 GMT
Content-length: 5858
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>     
<head>     
<title>Chavez: Clinton Welfare Flip: At Least He Landed in Right Spot  -- 5/22/96     
</title>     
</head>     
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">     
     
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>     
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><p><br>   
<i>   May 22, 1996</i><br>     
     
     
     
<h2> 
Clinton Welfare Flip: At Least He Landed in Right Spot
</h2>     
     
     
<a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">     
Linda Chavez     
</a>     
<p>
BETHESDA, Md. -- He may not look like an Olympic gymnast, but Bill 
Clinton has proved he's a real master of the triple somersault with 
his latest move on welfare reform. The man who campaigned on the 
promise of ending welfare as we know it -- and then vetoed two 
welfare-reform bills which did just that -- has once again reversed 
himself.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
On Saturday, the president announced he'll support a Wisconsin plan to 
abolish Aid to Families with Dependent Children (AFDC) and replace it 
with a mandatory work program.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Yet just months ago, the president and other administration officials 
excoriated Republicans in Congress as "radical" and "extremist" for 
proposing welfare reforms far more modest than Wisconsin's plan.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Under Republican Gov. Tommy Thompson's welfare reform, Wisconsin will 
eliminate traditional welfare and replace it with work. Women who 
apply for assistance in Wisconsin will receive job counseling and be 
expected to work in a regular job or in one subsidized by the state.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
For those who have few skills or little work experience, the state 
will provide community-service jobs or places in "sheltered workshops" 
which will provide work activities consistent with recipients' 
abilities.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
These changes in state law require the administration's approval 
before they can take effect, however, which is why the president's 
endorsement is so crucial. And requiring welfare mothers to work is 
still controversial in some circles -- especially among Democrats.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Welfare-rights activists who oppose the Wisconsin reforms argue that 
children will suffer if their mothers are forced off welfare and into 
jobs unless the state provides a myriad of expensive services, 
including job training and child care.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
And President Clinton cited the lack of sufficient money for training 
and child care in the congressional welfare-reform proposals when he 
vetoed them last winter.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
But working mothers who have never been on welfare receive little, if 
any, help with subsidized day care for their children, much less 
government-financed employment training.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Does it really make sense to provide greater benefits to those who 
have shown less initiative and responsibility than we do to women who 
struggle to balance work and family duties?
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
But some welfare advocates argue that mothers of young children 
shouldn't be forced to work at all. This argument might actually have 
carried some weight when most women stayed home to raise their 
children. Indeed, AFDC began in 1935 as a program to help women whose 
husbands had died or abandoned them, at a time when only about 8% of 
married women with children were in the labor force.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Today, however, 76% of married women with school-age children work, as 
do 62% of those with children under 6 years.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The great irony is that a larger percentage of married than single 
moms work. Only 57% of single mothers are in the workforce, including 
only 52% of those with children under 6. For nonworking single moms, 
Uncle Sam is the main provider. And women who bear children out of 
wedlock are far more likely than divorced mothers to end up on welfare 
and to stay there for long periods, sometimes indefinitely.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Clearly, something has gone wrong with a system that makes it easier 
for a woman to stay home to raise her children if she doesn't marry 
the father than if she does.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
At least in Wisconsin that may no longer be the case.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
It takes an election to get Bill Clinton to do the right thing. But 
for now, his latest welfare back flips have landed him in the right 
spot -- and he's likely to remain there at least for the rest of the 
campaign.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The trick for Republicans will be to use Clinton's Wisconsin decision 
to force his hand on a federal bill that puts in place some of the 
same reforms before the election.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
    
<P><P>     
<HR>     
<P>     
     
<i>     
<center>     
Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>     
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a>.     
     
</i>     
     
