<html><head><title>Chavez: The Coming Battle on Social Security
</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><i>November 1, 1995</i>
<hr>
<h2>The Coming Battle on Social Security</h2> 
<P><a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a></center>
<p><hr><P>
The continuing conflict over Medicare reform may be just a warm-up to 
the coming battle on Social Security.  Though few politicians want to 
talk about it, the Social Security system is anything but secure.  And 
if current demographic trends continue, those persons who are 25-50 
years-old today can forget about recouping their contributions into 
the system when they turn 65.
<P>
Social Security is one of the biggest give-away programs in the 
federal budget, yet the program remains almost universally popular and 
untouchable when it comes to budget-cutting.  Why?  Because most 
people -- both the elderly and younger workers -- have been sold a 
bill of goods.
<P>
Myth # 1. Social Security recipients are simply getting back in 
benefits what they and their employers put into the system in payroll 
taxes during their working lives.  
<p>
Actually, the average person retiring today will get back what he and 
his employers paid into the system within the first 4.5 years after 
retirement.  Since the average man will live 7.3  years after 
retirement age and the average woman 14 years, most beneficiaries will 
receive nearly 1.5 to 3 times what they contributed.
<p>
Myth # 2.  The Social Security Trust Fund operates like any other 
pension system, the money is put aside and invested to pay for future 
benefits.
<p>
Wrong.  In most private pension plans, the employer/employee 
contributions are saved and invested to provide  the actual benefits 
workers will receive from the plan.  But Social Security benefits are 
financed differently, on a pay-as-you-go system.  Benefits don't come 
from retirees' own contributions, but rather from the contributions of 
those who are still working.  
<p>
The so-called Trust Fund isn't really a separate fund at all, but a 
bookkeeping device.  And the money supposedly "in" the fund isn't 
invested but used by the government to pay for other government 
programs.  The fund supposedly "receives" long-term Treasury bonds in 
return for this "investment."  
<p>
In essence, the government borrows from itself and promises to pay it 
back at some later time.  But what that really means is that the 
government borrows from taxpayers, in this case future taxpayers, and 
most likely will pay it back by raising taxes down the line.
<p>
Myth # 3 Even if Social Security is a pay-as-you-go system, the next 
generation will be willing to pay for the program that, after all, 
takes care of its own parents.
<p>
The problem is the next generation of retirees had fewer children than 
previous generations.  The current system depends on a pyramid 
financing scheme.  In order to pay for the present level of benefits, 
3 workers contribute payroll taxes to pay for 1 retiree's benefits.  
But the ratio of workers to retirees is actually shrinking slightly.  
When the baby-boomers retire, there will be only 2 workers per retiree 
available to pay taxes for the same benefits.  Something will have to 
give: either benefits will significantly drop or taxes will rise 
dramatically.
<p>
Myth # 4.  The elderly are the most vulnerable and poorest members of 
society who can least afford to have their government benefits 
trimmed.
<p>
Certainly there are many poor elderly people in the U.S.  But the 
economic condition of the elderly has actually improved dramatically 
over the last few decades, while that of children has declined at the 
same time.  There has been a large shift in wealth in recent years 
from the young and working aged to the elderly, and government 
programs have been chiefly responsible.  
<p>
Although those aged 65 or older are only 12.5% of the population, they 
receive more than one-third of all federal dollars in benefits, 
regardless of actual need.  Americans rail against welfare programs 
for poor women and their children -- especially Aid to Families with 
Dependent Children, which accounts for only about 1% of federal 
spending -- but never imagine that both Social Security and Medicare 
are really welfare programs for the elderly, including those who are 
wealthy and have no need of subsidies.
<p>
It's time Americans of all ages face up to the fact that current 
elderly programs will bankrupt America. Radically reforming Social 
Security is not only necessary, but just and fair.
<hr width="50%">
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a><p><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</body>

</html>  
