<html>
<head>
<title>du Pont: A New Medicare: A Better Deal for the Elderly -- 4/28/96</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">

<hr>

  
<center>
<h2>A New Medicare: <br>A Better Deal for the Elderly
 </h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/dupont.html"><i>Pete du Pont</i> </a>
</center><hr>








<P>

<P>




<P>
Medicare, the government health care program for older 
Americans, currently serves 32 million people and costs about $180 
billion a year.  Medicare recipients pay $19 billion in premiums and the 
rest comes from a federal payroll tax.
<P>
Often the health care provided isn't very good. One reason is that 
the government pays doctors and hospitals providing the care only about 
70% of its cost, so doctors don't want to serve Medicare patients. As a 
result, there are longer waits for care, and sometimes a lack of care. So 
health care is being rationed to some of the elderly.
<P>
The quality of care may be lower, too, since hospitals and doctors 
are paid the same fee regardless of the quality of care provided.  For 
example, if a doctor is paid a fixed amount to implant a pacemaker, why 
not implant the cheapest one available and pocket the difference?
<P> 
 Finally, new medical technology is slow to be approved by the 
Medicare bureaucracy, so the elderly often get "old medicine."
<P>
 Even with all these efforts to limit costs, Medicare is proving to 
be very, very expensive.  According to the Clinton administration and 
Medicare Trustees, Medicare as it now operates will run out of money in 
less than seven years.
<P>
  By 2000, under current budget projections, Medicare will spend 
almost $250 billion, about 13% of the entire federal budget.  The deficit 
in Medicare Part A (hospital insurance) and the general revenue 
contribution to Medicare Part B (insurance for physicians' fees and other 
expenses) will be adding almost $150 billion to the total federal deficit.  
<P>
 Financial problems will quickly grow worse after that.  By the 
time those entering the workforce today retire, the Medicare payroll tax 
will need to be three to seven times higher than now.  The annual 
premiums paid by the elderly will be about $4,400 to $8,600 per couple 
instead of today's $1,000.
<P>	
 It doesn't have to be that way.  One simple and popular reform 
proposal offers a solution:  allowing the elderly the choice of substituting 
a Medical Savings Account and private insurance for their current 
Medicare coverage.
<P>
 Under one version of this proposal, Medicare beneficiaries 
would have the right to receive 95% of average Medicare spending per 
beneficiary and put it into a Medical Savings Account (MSA).  Retirees 
could also contribute the funds they must currently pay for Medicare 
premiums, supplemental Medigap insurance, and out-of-pocket health 
expenses.
<P>
  For the average retiree, these would total close to $9,000 next 
year.  The retiree would use part of these funds to purchase catastrophic 
insurance covering all expenses over a high deductible (say $2,000 or 
$3,000).  The retiree would have at least $2,000-$3,000 remaining in the 
account, which would then be used to pay expenses below the deductible, 
including HMO or other private health care insurance coverage if they 
prefer.  Any unspent MSA funds could then be withdrawn at the end of 
the year for any purpose, or saved for future medical expenses.
<P>
 With MSAs, the quality of elderly health care would quickly 
begin to improve.   Patients would be free to choose the doctors and 
hospitals that would provide the quality health care they prefer.  The 
elderly who exercised the MSAs would also have complete catastrophic 
coverage, which Medicare does not provide.  Medicare coverage runs out 
after a certain number of days of hospital care, and other benefits are 
similarly limited.  But with an MSA, the elderly can buy a catastrophic 
policy that pays all costs over their chosen deductible.
<P>
 Most important, since people would effectively be spending 
their own funds out of the MSAs for non-catastrophic health care, they 
would have excellent incentives to eliminate waste and inefficiency and 
control their own costs.  Since doctors and hospitals would be receiving 
100% payment for their services instead of 70% under today's Medicare, 
they in turn would compete to reduce costs to attract elderly patients 
trying to conserve their MSA funds.  The result would be lower costs for 
Medicare.
<P>
 Several private sector employers have already adopted MSAs 
for their workers and achieved dramatic cost savings of 30%-40% and 
more as a result.  To the extent Medicare beneficiaries chose MSAs, 
much of this cost savings would likely be achieved for Medicare as well.  
This would greatly help to reduce the burden of Medicare on the federal 
budget and its contribution to the overall deficit.  It would also help to 
solve the long term Medicare financing crisis. And since the individual 
gets 95% of average Medicare spending, the government saves an 
additional 5%, or more than $5 billion per year.	
<P>
  This proposal provides overwhelming benefits to the elderly, 
and would be enormously popular.  Yet, all of this can be achieved while 
actually saving the government substantial funds, and helping to solve the 
program's long term financing crisis.  Such a combination of advantages 
should be irresistible to policymakers.

<p>

<i>The National Center for Policy Analysis is a public policy research 
institute founded in 1983 and internationally known for its studies on 
public policy issues.  The NCPA is headquartered in Dallas, Texas, with 
an office in Washington, D.C.</i>
<P> 
[<a href="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi">Columnists</a>]
