<html>
<head>
<title>The End of Quotas Just in Time</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><i>July 27, 1995 </i>
<hr>

  

<h2>The End of Quotas Just in Time
 </h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/dupont.html"><i>Pete du Pont</i> </a>
</center><hr>










<p>

President Clinton's  "full-throated" (Washington Post) and "near- evangelical" (New York Times) endorsement of affirmative action has set liberal hearts a flutter.
<p>
The University of California's Regents' vote to end race-based admission, hiring, and contracting set Rev. Jesse Jackson ablaze.
<p>
Over at the Judicial branch of government, cooler heads are prevailing. The U.S. Supreme Court has applied the brakes to affirmative action, questioning the constitutional validity of programs that guarantee jobs or contracts on the basis of race.  "Equal protection of the law is a personal right, not a group right," wrote Justice O'Connor.
<p>
Just in time, too, because for two decades government quotameisters have been cutting a broad swath through individual rights.
<p>
For example, the Pentagon sent out word that "special permission will be required for the promotion of all white men without disabilities."  The U.S. Forest Service, desperate to meet its goals for minority firefighters, earlier this year said in a job posting that it would only consider applicants "who do not meet standards."
<p>
Navy Secretary John Dalton has issued a policy that henceforth Naval officers will be commissioned "in a percentage approximately equal to the racial make-up of the populace."  Navy flight standards also seem to have been bent to meet quotas for women fighter pilots.
<p>
Nondiscrimination in hiring, promoting and in awarding government contracts is both right and a right.  But in practice, the Civil Rights Act of 1964 has been turned on its head by those charged with enforcing it.  Instead of trying to wipe out discrimination, they have mandated it.  The legislation that Senator Hubert Humphrey assured us could never be used to impose quotas has become a quota statute.
<p>
Affirmative action has become a zero-sum game in which gains for one group can only be made at the expense of other groups.  Setting aside a construction contract for one minority group takes opportunity away from others.  When the University of California at Berkeley sets different admission standards for Asian-American students (the policy the Regents just voted down) because too large a percentage of them would be admitted if only grades and test scores were used, Asians are disadvantaged and blacks gain.
<p>
Quotas also undermine the very minorities they are supposed to help.  In a recent issue of The New Democrat, Carol M. Swain, a black professor of politics and public policy at Princeton University, blamed affirmative action for promoting a "helpless victim" mentality that undermines self- respect and initiative.  She wrote:  "It says in effect that you, as a woman or minority, are less capable than a white male and will need special preference in order to compete successfully in a world dominated by white males."
<p>
As a result, a black or Hispanic or woman who is hired or is promoted to a position of responsibility has to overcome the suspicion on the part of others that he or she wouldn't be there except for a quota.  The resulting self-doubt can become an additional handicap in achieving success.
<p>
Justice Clarence Thomas, addressing school busing in the Kansas City desegregation case, was blunt:  "It never ceases to amaze me that the courts are so willing to assume that anything that is predominantly black must be inferior.  This position [that racial imbalances are unconstitutional] appears to rest upon the idea that any school that is black is inferior, and that blacks cannot succeed without the benefit of the company of whites."
<p>
Quotas are also an easy way out.  Quotameisters just calculate that the local population is 12% black, 7% Hispanic and 1% Asian-American, and demand that the makeup of everybody's workforce reflect those percentages.  Then businesses don't have to worry about searching for talented people, or recruiting them, or looking for human potential and helping to develop it.  That takes work.  It's much easier just to hire by the numbers.
<p>
Thus we have incidents like the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission's Chicago office spending seven years unsuccessfully  suing a Korean-owned janitorial service because more than 5% of its workforce was Korean and 95% of the Chicago labor pool was not.
<p>
Trying to end racial or sexual discrimination by giving preferences to one group at the expense of another is like trying to level a table.  If you cut too much off one leg, you have to cut off the others to even things out. And if you make a mistake, you can always trim a little more here or there.  But soon the table is useless.
<p>
So far, there is no indication that the government is going after National Basketball Association teams because they have such a high percentage of black (or tall) players.  Nor does anyone seem to be investigating why seven of the ten best lifetime batting averages of all time belong to left- handed hitters.  Maybe Justice O'Connor spoke just in time.
<p>
The National Center for Policy Analysis is a public policy research institute founded in 1983 and internationally known for its studies on public policy issues.  The NCPA is headquartered in Dallas, Texas, with an office in Washington, D.C.
<p>
<centnter>
<br>

