<head>
<title>A Program in need of a Crisis</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><i> Thursday, August 10, 1995 </i>
<hr>

  

<h2>A Program in Need of a Crisis
 </h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/dupont.html"><i>Pete du Pont</i> </a>
</center><hr>










<p>
<p>
When the politicians in Washington suddenly discover a new issue, do you ever wonder about the facts?  You should, because sometimes the facts contradict what the politicians are saying.
<p>
Remember "Alar"?  It turned out there was no apple pesticide problem - the politicians made up the scare.
<p>
Likewise, the Congress mandated $4 billion a year in acid rain mitigation, even though the most comprehensive environmental study in history concluded there was "no evidence of a general or unusual decline of forest in the United States or Canada due to acid rain." And the problem of global warming, according to the Washington Post, "appears to be heading toward solution before [researchers] can find any solid evidence that serious harm was or is being done."
<p>
This summer saw another example of the facts contradicting the politicians:  children's vaccinations.
<p>
In 1993, right in the middle of the great health care debate when President Clinton was trying to scare everyone (with some success) into believing the country's health care system had imploded, the president proposed and the Congress passed a costly new program that would  create an elaborate new distribution system to provide vaccines free of  charge to poor children, the Vaccines for Children Program (VFC).
<p>
Never mind that about half of all childhood vaccines were already being provided free through public health clinics.  The Clintons - and I use the plural intentionally - needed to persuade people that a health care crisis had arisen.  The president pointed to a measles epidemic between 1989 and 1991 that took the lives of more than 100 children in the United States.  And he argued that the reason many children weren't vaccinated was the cost - drug companies were pursuing "profits at the expense of our children."
<p>
But the facts tell a very different story.  In May 1994, for example, the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) published a study of measles immunization of 2-year-olds in Mississippi during the time of the outbreak.
<p>
What did the researchers find out about this rural southern state with a large black population and below-average incomes?  First, that the statewide measles immunization rate of 2-year-olds was 87% (ranging from 79% to 97% according to the geographical district).  While 87% isn't perfect, it's far from being a crisis justifying a $500 million federal vaccination program.
<p>
Moreover, immunization rates were "similar for white and black children in each health district and for the state as a whole."  So there is no racial discrimination problem.
<p>
But what about the poor, rural population? They're the ones who have to drive the farthest to get the immunizations, so doesn't a large rural population point to the need for the president's new distribution scheme? No, because "the level of vaccine coverage was significantly higher in districts with lower population densities (i.e., rural) and those with higher per capita incomes," according to the report.
<p>
So who's left?  Lower-income people living in urban areas - those most likely to have access to public clinics where free vaccines have always been available.
<p>
But the most significant finding of the JAMA study is this:  half of those measles cases contracted during the outbreak in Mississippi "occurred in unimmunized children too young to receive the MMR (measles, mumps, rubella) vaccine."  (Emphasis added)  It's pretty difficult to blame those "greedy" drug companies for the fact that many children were too young to get the vaccine.
<p>
Now, two years after the VFC's inception, comes a General Accounting Office (GAO) report finding that the VFC's newly created distribution scheme, meant to make the vaccines more accessible to poor children, is not working.   For example, 14 states were prohibited by state law from distributing free vaccines to private physicians, the software needed to process orders was defective, and the Centers for Disease Control could not ensure that the program would serve only entitled children.  Of seven  major implementation tasks considered by the GAO, six  "remained incomplete and problematic."
<p>
Most significant, the GAO found the cost of vaccines had never been a major barrier to immunizations.  A different 1994 JAMA study, done prior to the GAO report, had come to a similar conclusion.  It found that the "provision of free vaccine alone will not guarantee adequate immunization of poor urban children."
<p>
The truth is that the administration created and promoted the VFC program from political necessity rather than medical necessity.  As with his grander attempt to restructure the entire health care system, President Clinton needed to impart a crisis atmosphere, and he succeeded -- for a time, anyway.  Now that the crisis mentality and his health care plan have died, so should the VFC program.
<p>
The National Center for Policy Analysis is a public policy research institute founded in 1983 and internationally known for its studies on public policy issues.  The NCPA is headquartered in Dallas, Texas, with an office in Washington, D.C.
<p>
For more information:  Windi Fuller or Glenn Mitchell 214/386-6272<p>

<p>
<center>
<br>

