<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier: Spiritual Renewal -- 1/2/96</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
January 2, 1996
<br></i><hr>
<h2>Vincent Foster</h2></center><P> 

[More than two years after it occurred, the death of White House Counsel 
Vincent Foster continues to raise troubling questions.]
<p>
The body of White House Counsel Vincent Foster was discovered in Fort 
Marcy Park across the Potomac River from Washington DC, at 6 p.m. on 
July 20, 1993. The U.S. Park Police found a pistol in Foster's hand and 
quickly ruled the death a suicide. Nevertheless, a poll conducted by Time 
magazine and CNN two years later revealed that 65 percent of Americans 
do not accept the official verdict in the case.
<p>
Government investigators have ignored evidence suggesting that Foster's 
body was dumped in Fort Marcy Park, and that he may not have taken his 
own life. The suspicious nature of Foster's death, and his connection to 
the Whitewater and Travelgate scandals, make this one of the biggest 
news stories of the 1990s. Yet, only one reporter in America is 
investigating the Foster death on a full time basis. Christopher Ruddy 
began his probe as an investigative reporter for the New York Post in 
1993 . Now associated with the Pittsburgh Tribune-Review, Ruddy 
continues his one-man crusade to find out what really happened to "the 
highest ranking federal official in more than 30 years [to die] under very 
suspicious circumstances."
<p>
Ruddy summarizes the many inconsistencies in the case in a new report 
available from the nonprofit Western Journalism Center entitled Vincent 
Foster: The Ruddy Investigation. Ruddy points out that a confidential 
Secret Service memo written on the night of Foster's death stated that 
"U.S. Park Police discovered the body of Vincent Foster in his car." He 
says a senior Park Police investigator admitted that she and her 
colleagues reached a verdict of suicide "prior to going up and looking at 
the body."
<p>
Three handwriting experts have declared Foster's so called suicide note a 
forgery. "A note torn into 28 pieces, leaving no fingerprints and said to 
have been written by Foster, was found almost a week after his death," 
says Ruddy, but it lacks the contents typical of a suicide note -- no 
mention of death, no farewell to loved ones, and so on. The lack of an 
accounting for Foster's whereabouts during the last five hours of his life 
is also problematic, says Ruddy, noting that "no one came forward to 
claim they had seen him alive at the park or even around Washington, 
that fateful afternoon."<p>

The suicide scene itself was atypical. Foster's body was neatly arranged. 
"The fired bullet was never found. No one heard the fatal shot," says 
Ruddy. "Trace analysis of Foster's shoes at the FBI lab found not a speck 
of soil on his shoes or clothing despite a 700-foot-plus trek through the 
heavily wooded park."
<p>
All Ruddy wants is straight answers to some simple questions. "If Foster 
didn't shoot himself . . . who did? Where? How did he really die? These 
are the questions investigators should have asked," says Ruddy. "Their 
answers lead to other, logical questions about the strong evidence that the 
body was moved to the park."
<p>
(NOTE: For a copy of Vincent Foster: The Ruddy Investigation, call the 
Western Journalism Center at 1-800-711-1968.)

<p>                           <P>
