<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  "No-Win Situation" in Bosnia  -- 1/8/96</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
January 8, 1996<br></i><hr>
<h2>"No-Win Situation" in Bosnia </h2></center><P> 
 
[Syndicated columnist Charles Krauthammer says that sending U.S.  
troops to Bosnia is a "serious mistake" and a "no-win situation."]  
  <P>
In a recent issue of The Weekly Standard, Charles Krauthammer argues  
that U.S. involvement in Bosnia will have one of two unacceptable  
outcomes. Either it will end in "a humiliating retreat . . . after some  
incident involving a major loss of American life and cries from the  
Congress and the American people for withdrawal. Or, more likely, we  
will persevere, indeed escalate our involvement, send more troops to  
protect existing troops and be caught in a long-term, static, and defensive  
deployment with painful losses, ambiguous rules of engagement,  
escalating friction among NATO allies . . . and no way out."  
  <P>
Krauthammer says American troops are going into Bosnia with "no  
definable objective, no identifiable enemy, no exit strategy." Being the  
"sole remaining superpower" and having the "finest, most powerful  
military" do not obligate the United States to be the world's peacekeeper.  
"It is decidedly not the role of a superpower to place itself between the  
combatants in a civil war of marginal importance to the world balance of  
power . . . among unreconciled parties who have already shown a  
propensity for killing and kidnapping peacekeepers."  
  <P>
"Peacekeeping is the job of small countries with no particular interest in  
the outcome of a conflict," says Krauthammer. "It is far harder for a  
superpower to remain neutral, and even harder to be perceived as neutral,  
in most conflicts. And, in the Bosnian war, in particular, the United States  
has been decidedly not neutral. We have made our sympathies with the  
Bosnian Muslim side abundantly clear in our declarations, in our use of  
air power, and indeed in our promises to arm the Bosnian government  
even as we act as peacekeepers."  
  <P>
"If the combatants in Bosnia are serious about ending the fighting and  
accepting roughly the distribution of territory and roughly the balance of  
power now on the ground, then they should do it and enforce it  
themselves," says Krauthammer. "If they are not, then there is no peace to  
keep. And between such antagonists is no place to interpose American  
troops."  
  <P>
Krauthammer concedes that "reneging" on the promise to deploy troops  
"would be a blow to NATO," but contends that "following through and  
actually sending the troops would be worse." He describes as "nonsense"  
the argument that "we must intervene in Bosnia because of the  
continuing, indeed intensifying, threat the war poses to European  
stability." He says "the war is in fact contracting" and that the great  
nations of Europe have no reason to make war "over the control of this  
cursed, tragic piece of land." While acknowledging that American  
credibility is damaged "whenever the United States makes a commitment  
and then reneges on it," Krauthammer insists that the blame belongs to  
"the administration that made that foolish promise without proper  
reflection." Congress, on the other hand, should be applauded for "trying  
to avert the consequences of that ill-considered promise."

<p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>

