<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  Musical Madness -- 1/17/96</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists//townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> 
<br>
January 17, 1996<br></i><hr><h2>Musical Madness</h2>
</center>
<P>
["Popular musical messages contribute to an increasingly violent and 
morally bankrupt society. "]
<P>
In a new report called Bringing Out the Worst in Us: The Frightening 
Truth About Violence, the Media, and Our Youth, Focus on the Family 
research manager Robert Waliszewski argues that "musical messages are 
capable of planting dangerous ideas in the minds of young people or 
fueling those which already exist." He provides samples of some of the 
more offensive rap and heavy-metal lyrics and cites documented accounts 
of the violent crimes they've inspired. Although there is much evidence 
that "a strong correlation exists between a steady diet of mayhem and the 
urge to act on it," Waliszewski concedes that "no one knows what the 
cumulative effect will be when a young person consumes a steady diet of 
violent music."
<P>
Musically inspired sexual assaults and murders are just the tip of the 
iceberg. "For every teenager who makes the 6 o'clock news by carrying 
out an act of violence, there are thousands more whose values are being 
fashioned subtly through disturbing musical messages," says 
Waliszewski. "They're learning that demeaning women is not only 
acceptable, but [even] preferable to treating women with respect. They're 
hearing accounts that glorify serial killers and praise drive-by shootings. 
They're being bombarded with the messages that parents and other 
authorities are not worthy of respect; that life revolves around drugs, 
money, and perverse forms of sexual activity -- to be obtained by force, if 
necessary."
<P>
The content of contemporary music is qualitatively different from that of 
even the recent past. "Three decades ago, not one popular song 
encouraged robbery, rape, murder, assaults, or using weapons to settle 
disputes," says Waliszewski. "In today's popular music, all these themes 
can be found -- and worse! Nothing is taboo. Unfortunately, America's 
streets and neighborhoods increasingly reflect this fact. What's more, 
since violent lyrics are a relatively new phenomenon, no one knows the 
results of raising a generation on this type of musical diet. In addition, 
teenagers have greater access to (and are listening to) far more music than 
they have in past generations." Waliszewski notes that, by the end of high 
school, the average teenager has listened to more than 10,000 hours of 
rock music.
<P>
Violent crime increased by over 500 percent during the three decades 
ending in 1990. There may be a host of factors contributing to this social 
pathology, but "violence in the media" is certainly one of them. "Music 
industry insiders often shirk responsibility by saying their music reflects 
society but does not impact it," Waliszewski observes. "Some music 
industry insiders have argued that, as performers and 'actors on the stage,' 
musicians cannot be held responsible for their fans' criminal behavior. 
Their anti-social messages are not to be taken seriously because...they 
don't actually mean what they say."  Such claims are disingenuous at best. 
Whether they know what they're doing or not, the purveyors of this 
madness should be held accountable for the damage they've done to an 
entire generation of young Americans. 
<p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
