<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  Filth on Film -- 1/18/96</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
January 18, 1996
<br></i><hr>
<h2>Filth on Film</h2></center><P>

["By the time the average child leaves elementary school, he will have 
witnessed 8,000 murders and i00, 000 other acts of violence on TV."]
<P>
"TV, if used for responsible purposes, can have a positive impact," says 
Focus on the Family research manager Robert Waliszewski. "Yet, 
positive television is only a small portion of what America is watching. 
For many, the 'education' received from televised programming can have 
a detrimental effect." Waliszewski cites a 1993 report by the American 
Psychological Association that declared emphatically that "higher levels 
of viewing violence on television are correlated with increased 
acceptance of aggressive attitudes and increased aggressive behavior." 
Surveys of prison inmates imprisoned for violent crimes reveal that as 
many as a third "reported having consciously imitated criminal 
techniques learned from television pro ,rams."
<P>
In a new report called Bringing Out the Worst in Us: The Frightening 
Truth About Violence, the Media, and Our Youth, Waliszewski argues 
that "television's preoccupation with sex, violence, and sexualized 
violence would have been unthinkable in the minds of its early pioneers," 
adding that "public sentiment would not have embraced the likes of The 
Playboy Channel, MTV, Spice, HBO and Showtime." But ugliness and 
depravity are pervasive on television today, and "TV talk shows are just 
the tip of the iceberg. With its offering of offensive sitcoms, cartoons, 
made-for-TV-movies, film releases and graphic news footage, television 
has sunk to new lows."
<P>
Waliszewski warns that "television transmits values that are opposite to 
those being taught at home," forcing children "to choose which message 
to believe." Alarming increases in juvenile delinquency rates would seem 
to suggest that television is winning the values battle. "TV receives the 
lion's share of a young person's attention -- and does so in their most 
impressionable years," says Waliszewski. "By the time the average 
American child graduates [from] high school, he or she will have spent 
nearly 20,000 hours in front of a television" -- nearly twice the amount of 
time spent in school.
<P>
Much of the trash on television is recycled garbage from Hollywood. 
Waliszewski laments the passing of the Production Code, which 
discouraged directors from giving in to their baser instincts. "Since the 
days of silent movies, the power of a motion picture, with its potential to 
negatively impact society, has not gone unnoticed. For that reason, 
industry pioneers drafted a self-regulatory code of ethics in 1930 that 
governed the content of movies," prohibiting films that undermined the 
sanctity of home and marriage, disparaged the clergy, blasphemed, or in 
any way lowered the standards of viewers. That code has long since been 
abandoned.
<P>
Waliszewski concedes that "films do not 'cause' anyone to commit 
destructive acts. However, they can, and do, shape the values of the 
watchers." He notes that films like Natural Born Killers and Menace II 
Society have encouraged numerous impressionable viewers to imitate the 
unspeakable violence they glorified. But the ill effects don't end there. 
"For many undetermined others, their values were molded -- causing a 
desensitization toward violence and a loss of respect for society's laws 
and lawkeepers."
<p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
