<head>
<title>Duplantier:  Idahoans Lead Health Care Reform  -- 2/4/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

February 4, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Idahoans Lead Health Care Reform</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>"Can you name the two most progressive communities in America? When it comes to innovative approaches to health care, Jersey City, New Jersey and Ada County, Idaho are true trailblazers. </i></blockquote>
<P> 
In 1994, Jersey City, New Jersey became the first local government in 
America to offer its employees the health insurance option of Medical 
Savings Accounts (MSAs). Fewer than 200 of the city's nearly 3,000 
employees signed on at the outset, but even that small number saved Jersey 
City $21,000 in insurance premiums in the first three months that the plan 
was in use. In 1995, Ada County, Idaho followed suit with an MSA-based 
health insurance plan that County Commissioner Gary Glenn says was 
"designed to provide Ada County employees significantly enhanced health 
insurance coverage at a significantly reduced cost to the taxpayer." 
Roughly 170 out of 900 Ada County employees agreed to switch to MSAs, 
saving taxpayers $87,000 a year. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Providing enhanced coverage at a reduced cost may sound like "voodoo 
economics," but the explanation is simple. MSA plans pay 100 percent of a 
policyholder's health care expenses, but rely on a high deductible to keep 
costs down. The high-deductible policies are much cheaper than traditional 
low-deductible plans. Part of the money saved goes into Medical Savings 
Accounts set up for employees. Workers use the MSAs to pay their minor 
medical bills until they reach the deductible. Because policyholders get to 
keep whatever funds are left in their MSAs at the end of the year, they 
have a strong incentive to dicker with their doctors, to take better care 
of themselves, and to forgo unnecessary tests and treatment. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
An editorial in the Idaho Statesmen last summer described Medical Savings 
Accounts as "a great way to save money, promote lower overall health-care 
costs, and make consumers a more active and equal partner in the health 
equation." An MSA plan "can save money because it encourages workers to 
shop around. Bargain hunters can motivate hospitals and doctors to 
compete," said the newspaper. "As long as medical providers and insurance 
companies are running the show, consumers have little control over cost and 
little incentive to worry about it." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Ada County Commissioner Gary Glenn thinks the Medical Savings Account is 
"the wave of the future" and takes pride in his county's status as "the 
second public employer in the nation to try this option." An MSA plan "puts 
the patient in charge," says Glenn, who insists that "Americans are as 
capable of making decisions about health care as they are about every other 
product and service they buy." Everyone's a winner with MSAs. "Taxpayers 
win because they will have to pay less to cover their public employees," 
says Glenn. "Employees win because they have the freedom to make their own 
healthcare decisions and maybe save some money in the process. And the 
country wins because it will bring down the cost of health care in 
general." 
 <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




