<head>
<title>Duplantier: MARDI GRAS -- 2/20/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>


<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
February 20, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2>Mardi Gras</h2>


<i><blockquote>
Today is Mardi Gras in New Orleans. As tractors tow the papier-mache 
and crepe-covered floats of the Rex parade down oak-lined St. Charles 
Avenue to Canal Street, parade-goers of all ages will shout their 
traditional plea to the trinket-laden riders: "Throw me something, 
Mister!"
</blockquote></i>

<P>
Everyone's a beggar on Carnival Day in New Orleans, pandering for 
handouts that come in the form of cast-metal doubloons, strings of 
multicolored beads, and oversized plastic cigars, toothbrushes and other 
oddities. It's a day of self-indulgence, and it's all in fun, but it takes 
hundreds of well-trained policemen, posted at every corner of the six-
mile parade route, to keep the merriment from getting out of hand. As 
much as New Orleanians love their Mardi Gras, you'd be hardpressed to 
find anyone who isn't glad to see it end on Ash Wednesday, the 
beginning of Lent.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Imagine people hanging out in the streets all year long waiting for 
someone to toss them a few freebies, having nothing better to do in the 
meantime other than look for ways to get into trouble. A single day of 
community-wide excess may serve as a relief valve for the pressures that 
build up during the year, but socially-sanctioned self-indulgence on a 
continuing basis makes no sense at all. Yet, that's just what we have with 
our federal welfare system.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Robert Rector of the Heritage Foundation argues that welfare "reduces 
work effort and promotes illegitimacy and poverty-prone single-parent 
families." The government dole is "extremely efficient at replacing self-
sufficiency with dependence, but relatively ineffective in raising incomes 
and eliminating poverty." Welfare is especially detrimental to children -- 
increasing the dropout rate and the unwed pregnancy and delinquency 
rates, and reducing longterm earning potential.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Foreign aid is nothing more than international welfare -- a global, year-
long Carnival -- and the effects are just as harmful. "Not only has the 
U.S. foreign aid program failed to promote economic growth in less 
developed countries, but many recipient countries are worse off because 
of it," say Bryan Johnson and Thomas Sheehy, also of the Heritage 
Foundation. They argue that, "instead of helping poor countries lift 
themselves out of poverty, aid often impedes their economic growth 
while damaging their fragile economies."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Maybe it's time the federal government took a tip from the City of New 
Orleans. If the politicians in Washington are determined to continue 
offering handouts and encouraging self-destructive behavior, let them 
confine this madness to a single day of the year. Let all the recipients of 
government largesse -- from individual entitlements to corporate 
subsidies to foreign aid -- gather in Washington for an annual one-day 
blowout. Let them jockey for position along the streets of the nation's 
capital as they wait for costumed congressmen to roll past on decorated 
floats. Let them all scream "Throw me something, Mister!" at the top of 
their lungs and fight among themselves for the goodies tossed their way. 
Then they can go home and behave themselves for the rest of the year.



<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
