<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier: SPACE ACADEMY -- 2/23/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>


<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
February 23, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2>Space Academy</h2>


<i><blockquote>
Some day in the not too distant future, you may get to watch your child 
or grandchild graduate from the U.S. Space Academy. On that proud 
day, you can both thank Lt. General Daniel Graham for making that 
opportunity possible.

</blockquote></i>

<P>
Lt. General Daniel Graham had become convinced towards the end of 
his life that U.S. space policy "needed fundamental overhaul. Space had 
become a ravenous consumer of resources when it should have become a 
source of national wealth and a bastion of national security," he 
lamented in his autobiography, Confessions of a Cold Warrior Graham 
recognized that new and emerging technology could "make the 
taxpayers' space investments provide a substantial return," if only the 
government could be persuaded to "open space to the general public and 
the private sector." Advances in technology had "removed the principal 
constraints on the pursuit of practical goals in space, and enabled both 
commercial and government programs that would be well-supported by 
the public."


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The commercial exploitation of space is no longer just a dream. If 
Americans want to capitalize on the boundless possibilities, however, we 
must plan accordingly. "No U.S. space policy, however well-formulated, 
can bear fruit without attention to the people who will be called upon to 
carry out the policy," General Graham warned. "Space efforts require a 
constant input of bright and properly educated young people into those 
sectors of government, industry and commerce that deal with space."

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Graham knew that generating "enthusiasm for space among young 
people" would be simple enough. "They want to be a part of the grand 
adventure of space activity," he observed. "But, beyond getting them 
excited, we have little advice to give them about how to realize their 
dreams except to advise excelling in one or another hard-science 
discipline." Graham's visionary solution was "a Space Academy along 
the lines of the U.S. Merchant Marine Academy where young 
Americans, and perhaps youngsters from other lands, could be steeped in 
the disciplines pertinent to space. They could be graduated with a 
bachelor's degree in space science, ready for employment in the 
aerospace industry, commercial space enterprises, or government civil 
and military space programs."

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
General Graham envisioned a comprehensive program of space 
scholarship, including disciplines such as "space medicine, space law, 
space diplomacy, space construction, and space literature." He saw "no 
difficulty whatever in establishing a space-oriented curriculum for the 
cadets of a Space Academy meeting all necessary criteria for the 
granting of degrees." He also knew that "the standards for entry into 
such an academy could be set very high and still not accommodate all 
young people who would apply and qualify. A student body with 
computer literacy, technical aptitude, physical fitness and high personal 
standards would be easily assembled, as well as a competent, highly 
motivated faculty." General Graham predicted that "graduates of such a 
Space Academy would be in great demand, and the aspirations of young 
people interested in a career in space-related activity could be channeled 
effectively."

<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




