<head>
<title>Duplantier: UNION TACTICS -- 2/27/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>


<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
February 27, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2>Union Tactics</h2>


<i><blockquote>
"The purpose of all cartels is to raise prices above competitive levels and 
to redistribute income from consumers to cartel members. When unions 
successfully raise the price of labor above free-market levels, much of the 
employers' higher labor costs are passed on to consumers."
</blockquote></i>

<P>
Trade unions have often been described as "cartels of workers which 
collude to push their wages above free-market levels," observes Thomas 
DiLorenzo in a recent issue of The Freeman, the monthly journal of the 
Foundation for Economic Education. "Competition and the entry of new 
(and lower-priced) competitors are the bane of all cartels." That's why 
unions strive "to block competition from nonunion workers through 
special-interest legislation and regulation, and by committing acts of 
violence and intimidation against nonunion workers."


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Warehouse clubs, hypermarkets, and nonunion chains make grocery 
union organizers see red. The avowed objective of these organizers is "to 
either raise the prices of nonunion grocery stores or drive those stores 
into bankruptcy." DiLorenzo observes that "driving one's competitors out 
of business may be good for aspiring monopolists, but is bad for 
consumers and those workers" whose companies are targeted for 
destruction. "Low-income Americans will be hurt the most, as they 
always are when prices rise." With their typically low profit margins, 
grocery chains are especially vulnerable to "union harassment 
campaigns."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The preferred tactic among grocery union organizers is pressuring a 
company "to accept a union without ever permitting its employees to vote 
on whether or not they want a union," says DiLorenzo. "This is a stark 
admission that, at least in the grocery industry, unionization cannot 
succeed if employees are allowed to vote on whether or not they want a 
union. Extortion has replaced organizing." Unable to win a fair election, 
union organizers "intimidate and threaten to extort employers until they 
sign a contract with the union without holding a union certification 
election."

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
DiLorenzo contends that the "flexible labor relations" essential to a 
company's efficiency are "rarely -- if ever -- found in unionized firms. 
Rigid job descriptions and restrictive work practices ratchet up costs and 
prices at unionized grocery chains, all to the detriment of the consumer. 
These higher costs and prices also threaten the job security of unionized 
employees who work for uncompetitive businesses."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The American workplace is "awash in regulations, most of which are 
impossible for mere humans to understand, let alone comply with." 
Unions have "taken advantage of this fact to impose regulatory costs on 
nonunion firms." DiLorenzo says that "regulation is so out of control that 
any business person in America, at any one time, is most certainly 
'guilty' of noncompliance with at least some regulations." He charges 
that unions "use regulation as a tool for extorting 'concessions' from 
nonunion employers, [including] recognition of the union without a 
representation election." DiLorenzo concludes that "deregulation of labor 
relations -- and of the economy in general -- is sorely needed if the 
American economy is to prosper."


<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




