<html>
<head>
<title> Duplantier: Revival of the Home Economy
-02/29/96
</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</B><br>
 
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier
</a><br>

    
February 29, 1996<br></i>
<h2>
Revival of the Home Economy
</h2>


<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>More than a million American children are now schooled at home. If 
present trends continue, homeschooling may one day become the 
preferred method of education in America, as it was before 1840.</I></BLOCKQUOTE><p>

The modern social-welfare state arose in the hundred years between 
1840 and 1940, assuming "nurturing functions that had throughout 
human history belonged to the family. The first and most important of 
these was education," writes Allan Carlson of the Rockford Institute in 
the February issue of The Family in America. "Beginning in the 1840s, 
in the same time and place as early industrialization, the common school 
movement, backed by compulsory education laws, took children out of 
the home for moral and practical training."

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The social-welfare state soon "captured other family functions as well," 
says Carlson. "Reform schools, the 'child saving' movement, the 
juvenile-justice system, and the vast child abuse and neglect apparatus 
all grew." Even child labor laws "further expanded the modern state's 
socialization of children's time." State-funded pension programs "erased 
other basic features of the family economy: security between the 
generations and care of the ill and infirm. Until modern times, grown 
children and other relatives provided security and support to elderly 
persons, particularly the indigent and the invalid. Adults bore an 
obligation, moral as well as social and legal, to care for their own; they 
also knew that their security might depend someday on the children they 
had reared and on the example they had set in giving care to their own 
parents. New systems of state pensions and health insurance shattered 
these security bonds between the generations of a family."

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


Allan Carlson contends that the growing homeschooling movement 
began in the 1970s as a reaction to "specific events -- federal efforts to 
regulate public and parochial education, Supreme Court decisions 
blessing the sexual revolution, the breakdown of discipline and standards 
in local schools, the appearance of books . . . encouraging a radical break 
with existing patterns of learning." These events, he says, "inspired a 
critical mass of pioneers to bring their children home. They soon 
discovered that, indeed, there's no place like home for the education of 
their children. These pioneer families also found that the nature of their 
family relationships changed, almost overnight. No longer mere 
consumers sharing the same roof and television set, they had become 
members of a learning enterprise who needed each other and who 
profited -- morally and practically -- from each other."


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


The pioneers of homeschooling made other pleasant discoveries. "Most 
of these families began to find ways to bring other functions home as 
well -- gardening, food preservation, or a family business -- and they 
tasted the satisfactions of an independence unknown to several American 
generations." Carlson argues that homeschooling "is the most promising 
effort at family institutional reconstruction undertaken in America 
during the last 150 years. The family, born to and naturally residing in 
the symbolic 'cottage,' then uprooted and ravaged by factory and state, 
has found a path back to its true home."




<P><P>

<p><i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.

</i>
<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>



