<head>

<title>Duplantier: Myths About Crime -- 03/14/96
</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="//townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier
</a><br>


March 14,  1996
</i><br>

<h2>
Myths About Crime
</h2>
<blockquote><i>
  
False ideas can have tragic consequences, say two respected criminologists, who argue that false ideas   
about crime have made the crime problem worse.  
</BLOCKQUOTE></I>
<P>  
 
"For the last quarter-century, a network of anti-incarceration, pro-prisoner analysts, activists, lawyers,   
lobbyists, journalists, and judges has perpetuated a number of false ideas about crime and punishment in   
the United States," say criminologists Charles Logan and John DiIulio. In an essay titled "Ten Deadly   
Myths About Crime and Punishment in the U.S.," published in a new book called Criminal Justice: The   
Legal System vs. Individual Responsibility, Logan and DiIulio argue that "the consequences of these false   
ideas have been quite tragic indeed." They've made it easier for criminals to indulge in crime, and they've   
concentrated crime "in economically distressed inner-city neighborhoods, inviting the criminal predators   
of these areas to repeatedly victimize their struggling underclass neighbors."  
  


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

One of the most enduring myths about crime in the United States is that it is caused by poverty. Logan and   
DiIulio report that many academic criminologists believe the myth that "capitalism produces pockets of   
poverty, inequality, and unemployment, which then foster crime. The solution [according to this view] is   
government intervention to provide jobs, stimulate the economy, and reduce poverty and other social ills."   
The truth, as it turns out, is quite the opposite. Poverty does not cause crime; crime, on the other hand,   
does cause poverty.  
  


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;



Logan and DiIulio note that "inner city areas where crime is rampant have tremendous potential for   
economic growth, given their infrastructure of railways, highways, electric power, water systems, and   
large supply of available labor. There is every reason for these areas to be wealthy," they say, "and, indeed,   
many of them have been rich in the past. But crime takes a terrible toll on physical, fiscal, and human   
capital, making it difficult to accumulate wealth and break out of the cycle of poverty. Criminals steal and   
destroy property, drive away customers and investors, reduce property values, and depreciate the quality of   
life in a neighborhood. Businesses close and working families move away, leaving behind a vacuum of   
opportunity." Inner cities need "physical protection and security" to make them viable again; instead, they   
get "economic intervention."  
  


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;



Another myth about crime in the United States is that prisons are filled with "petty offenders who should   
not be there." Logan and DiIulio say it isn't so. They cite data from the Bureau of Justice Statistics   
showing that "U.S. prison populations consist overwhelmingly of violent and repeat offenders."  
  

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

A third myth concerns the physical conditions within our nation's prisons. "There are two popular and   
competing images of American prisons," report Logan and Dilulio. "In one image, all or most prisons are   
hell holes. In the other image, all or most prisons are country clubs. Each image fits some prisons," they   
concede. "But the vast majority of prisons in the U.S. today are neither hell holes nor country clubs." They   
are what they're supposed to be: an effective means for isolating and punishing the criminal element. 


<P><P>
<HR>
<P>

<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to   
the preservation of our freeenterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free   
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: America's Future, 7800   
Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.  

</i>

