<head>
<title>Duplantier: Education Reform -- 4/4/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier

</a><br>


April 4, 1996
</i><br>

<h2>
Education Reform
</h2>



<P><blockquote><i>  
According to a national opinion poll conducted by USA Today in 
January, the quality of education in our country is the number-one 
concern for most Americans.
</blockquote></i>


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The quality of education in America is declining because "power in 
educational public policy rests with the producers, not the consumers," 
says Charles Greenawalt of the Commonwealth Foundation in 
Harrisburg, Pennsylvania. "Public education should serve the public 
interest and be accountable for its performance, but this is not the case." 
The education establishment "possesses near-monopoly control of this 
area of public policy." Greenawalt argues that the primary objective of 
this establishment is "not to improve and strengthen their performance, 
but to preserve itself, its clout, the status quo, and the resources at its 
disposal. This status quo is facilitated by complex layers of local, state, 
and federal regulations that apply to the schools and are implemented by 
overstaffed and generally unresponsive school district bureaucracies."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Greenawalt calls for "major shifts of authority and control over resources 
from producers to consumers and from experts to civilians. This means 
giving parents, taxpayers, elected officials, and community leaders far 
greater say over what schools need to accomplish, how the schools will 
be held accountable for this task, and how children and schools will be 
matched with one another." One way to do this is by "breaking vast 
school systems into smaller and more manageable units," says 
Greenawalt. "Consolidation in many areas has gone too far [resulting in] 
numerous school districts that are too large . . . to educate students 
effectively."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
For our educational system to be successful again, there must be 
reasonable standards of performance for students and teachers, genuine 
competition among the schools, and a renewed sense of professionalism 
among educators. Standards must "spell out in clear, unambiguous terms 
what students should learn and be able to do before they graduate," says 
Greenawalt. For standards to be effective, there must be "reliable and 
accurate assessments of student and school performance vis-a-vis those 
standards [which presupposes] trustworthy information about student 
performance [and] accountability mechanisms that will invoke 
meaningful consequences for all school personnel."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Noting that "children differ substantially in learning styles, temperament, 
and personal preference," Greenawalt argues that, "rather than attempting 
to standardize all schools, the state should welcome and promote 
educational diversity or pluralism. Let schools compete with one another 
based on their distinctive programs." According to Greenawalt, "School 
choice is an essential element for any comprehensive educational reform 
that is to be meaningful and long-lived. Families must be able to select 
their children's schools from a broad and varied array of choices."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Greenawalt says that teachers need to start thinking of themselves as 
individuals again. "Uniform salary schedules that treat everyone alike, 
regardless of performance, have no place in a true profession," he argues. 
"Likewise, the ability to strike and the presence of lifetime tenure are also 
antithetical to true professionalism. Schools must be operated for the 
benefit of their consumers -- the students -- not their producers."
<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




