<html><head>
<title>Duplantier: GAMBLING -- 4/19/96</title></head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
April 19, 1996
</i><br>
<h2>
GAMBLING
</h2>

<P><blockquote><i>  
Gaming fever has been sweeping the country for nearly 10 years now -- 
long enough for its true impact to be measured.
</blockquote></i>


<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
It starts with a state lottery, the proceeds pledged to education or some 
such worthy cause. Then the gambling boats roll up the river, supposedly 
regulated to lessen their mischief. At last, the land-based casinos appear, 
promising an economic renaissance for distressed communities. But it 
soon becomes apparent that legalized gambling is not the golden-egg-
laying goose it was claimed to be. The proceeds from the lottery are 
never as high as hoped for, and the worthy cause that was supposed to 
benefit often finds its annual appropriation from the state legislature 
reduced by a like amount. The riverboats, discovering all kinds of 
unanticipated navigational hazards, ultimately drop their anchors 
permanently. The land-based casinos usurp the patronage of local 
retailers and burden city coffers with the cost of vices generated by 
gaming.
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
"Casino gambling has been sold as the answer to economic problems 
everywhere it has been tried. But casinos serve as a gigantic sump, 
sucking sales from surrounding businesses," asserts Blake Hurst in the 
April issue of The American Enterprise magazine. "People who spend 
money at a casino can't spend it at [local restaurants], or the ballpark, or 
the amusement park. Gambling cannibalizes existing businesses, and the 
overall economic benefit to the economy is nil."
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The economic impact is actually negative, when the cost of social vices 
encouraged by gambling is factored in. One expert cited by Hurst 
"estimates that the average gambler with a problem has from $53,000 to 
$92,000 in gambling-related debt." Another authority on the subject 
reports that "the societal costs imposed by each problem gambler are over 
$13,000, with some estimates running as high as $52,000 annually." A 
survey of wanton wagerers "found that 75 percent of pathological 
gamblers have committed a felony to support their habit." According to 
Gamblers Anonymous, there are as many as 10 million problem gamblers 
in America.
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
"The economic case against gambling is clear," says Hurst. "Gambling 
doesn't create economic wealth, but rather transfers wealth from existing 
businesses to those lucky or influential enough to receive gambling 
monopolies from the state. Gambling increases political corruption and 
crime, and is a strikingly regressive means of raising revenue." That, 
believe it or not, is just the beginning of what's wrong with legalized 
gambling.
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Perhaps most damaging is the misleading message that legalized 
gambling sends to the citizenry, especially the young. "When the state 
removes the stigma from gambling by promoting it as a way to help 
education, people who have never gambled develop the habit. 
Governments may not be able to control vice, but surely they ought not to 
encourage it," says Blake Hurst. "When governments present riverboat 
casinos as economic development, they diminish those who build farms 
and factories. When states spend millions urging their citizens to play the 
lottery, they devalue the efforts of those who work hard and invest 
wisely."
<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




