<html><head>
<title>Duplantier: CHINA VS. CHILDREN -- 4/25/96</title></head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
April 25, 1996
</i><br>
<h2>
CHINA VS. CHILDREN
</h2>

<P><blockquote><i>  
Thousands of children will die in communist China's state-run 
orphanages this year, and it won't be any accident.

</blockquote></i>


<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
A former research specialist with the U.S. Census Bureau reports that 
"Chinese orphans are given sleeping pills instead of food, tied to cribs 
and chairs, left unchanged when soiled, denied medical care, and allowed 
to die of neglect." John Aird, author of a new book called "Slaughter of 
the Innocents: Coercive Birth Control in China," charges that "as many as 
90 percent of the children admitted to some institutions die there." That's 
because "China's leaders consider these children 'surplus' population. 
They try to prevent their birth by forced abortion." Chinese mothers-to-be 
who refuse to submit to government-mandated abortions are fined, 
beaten, imprisoned, and deprived of their homes and property. Even if 
they manage to deliver their babies alive, the newborns are still in danger. 
Writing in the April issue of The American Enterprise magazine, Aird 
asserts that Chinese doctors "work under orders by the authorities to kill 
all babies born without government permission."
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
More than 14 million abortions will be performed in communist China 
this year, and American taxpayers will pay for many of them. The U.S. 
Government contributes to the United Nations Fund for Population 
Activities, which supports China's coercive birth control program. "When 
the coercion in the program became undeniable in 1993, statements of 
protest were issued by the Clinton administration," notes Aird. "Yet 
President Clinton then went on to restore U.S. funding," which the 
Reagan administration had suspended in 1985.
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
"Strong words followed by weak actions sending a contrary signal have 
become the standard response of the Clinton administration to human 
rights offenses in China," observes Aird. Why aren't Americans 
protesting our government's support for China's murderous methods of 
undermining maternity? Aird speculates that "the unsubstantiated but 
widely held belief in a world population crisis has dulled public outrage 
over violations of reproductive freedom in China." He also suggests that 
"business interests intent on seeking profits by investing in China's 
booming economy do not want to risk strained relations with China over 
its human rights violations."
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Whatever the reason, the American people have not sufficiently 
publicized their repugnance for these policies, and the indifference of our 
government has been interpreted as a tacit endorsement of Chinese 
methods. "China's rulers apparently now feel free to expand tyrannical 
practices not only in birth control but also in the treatment of political 
dissidents," observes Aird, and we are in part to blame. "Although 
Chinese leaders say publicly that foreign criticism of China's human 
rights record . . . will not be accepted, China has in practice shown itself 
to be extremely sensitive to determined criticism backed by potential 
actions."
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Aird argues that the U.S. should "amend our immigration laws to 
recognize persecution under compulsory family planning programs as a 
basis for granting asylum. And we should withhold all funding from the 
United Nations Fund for Population Activities, the International Planned 
Parenthood Federation, and any other organization that provides 
assistance to China's harsh birth control program."
<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




