<head>
<title>Duplantier:  Government Bureaucracy  -- 5/2/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

May 2, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Government Bureaucracy</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
Few American taxpayers noticed much difference when thousands of 
government workers were declared nonessential and told to stay home 
until the federal budget crisis could be resolved. The only question 
was, how did so many unnecessary employees ever land a civil service 
job in the first place?
</i></blockquote>



<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
 In a recent editorial in the Washington Times, Gordon Jones of the 
Association of Concerned Taxpayers records the candid observations of 
one federal government employee regarding the low levels of 
productivity among his coworkers. "A large percentage of federal 
workers hurt rather than help get the work done," claims the 
exasperated civil servant, who for obvious reasons prefers to remain 
nameless. (We'll call him J.B., short for Jaundiced Bureaucrat.) J.B. 
complains that the worst one-third of the federal work force "actually 
drains energy and production from the efforts of their colleagues." 
Clearly, it would be better to pay such people to stay home; but, if 
that's the case, why pay them at all?
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The worst offenders were probably born that way, but there's something 
about working for the government that devitalizes even the most 
competent and conscientious civil servant. "Most federal workers did 
not start this way," says J.B. "Most walked in the door on their first 
day of federal service with a strong work ethic and an optimistic 
vision of serving their fellow citizens." Eventually, however, "the 
dysfunctional work environment takes its toll. First they lose their 
optimism, and then many lose their work ethic. Why? Because they 
observe many nonproductive troublemakers going undisciplined, and 
hardworking individuals going unrewarded. They learn that the 
personnel policies and processes encourage frivolous grievances and 
insupportable accusations. They learn that, in most cases, it is more 
helpful to your federal career to maintain the status quo."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Where are the managers, the persons responsible for motivating the 
work force and assessing individual performance? They're there, all 
right, but they're not doing their jobs. "The word 'management' is 
often used in the federal service by people who do not seem to 
understand what it means," observes J.B. "Individuals selected for 
their political connections instead of their management ability fill 
critical decision-making positions." Such persons are "guided by a 
perspective that demands a short-term 'fix' rather than a longer-term 
solution." The yes men they surround themselves with are happy to 
validate this self-serving approach.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
It may come as a surprise that many of the idlers feeding at the 
public trough in Washington feel themselves strangely put upon. 
Despite all evidence to the contrary, they're convinced that they're 
underpaid, compared to private-sector employees, and overworked. J.B. 
dismisses these complaints. "An amazing number of federal employees," 
he insists, "could not qualify for jobs in the private sector that 
paid anywhere near our current salaries." With 10 weeks' worth of 
vacation, holidays, and sick leave each year -- and precious little 
expected from him when he does show up at the office -- J.B. confesses 
that he is anything but underpaid and overworked.
 <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




