Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier:  Free Trade  -- 5/6/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

May 6, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Free Trade</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
Absolute free trade between countries does not exist. With the 
possible exception of the United States, all manage their trade to 
serve their own national interests.
</i></blockquote>
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Sovereign countries should establish trade policies that serve their 
own best interests, and they should expect their trading partners to 
do likewise. So-called free trade really makes no sense. Fair trade, 
however, is something different. All countries should be held to a 
certain minimal standard in their trade practices, and those that fail 
to live up to such a standard should be penalized. Many of the foreign 
countries that trade with America routinely resort to unfair 
practices, such as devaluing their currency, nationalizing U.S. 
property, violating agreements, stealing our patents and copyrights, 
and counterfeiting our money. It is absurd to advocate "free trade" 
with countries that engage in such disreputable practices.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
"Free trade" was the slogan used to persuade Congress to pass NAFTA 
and GATT, but what these treaties have done is put U.S. trade under 
the control of powerful new international bureaucracies. GATT created 
the World Trade Organization, which has a legislature, an executive 
branch, and a judicial system to control global trade. GATT is also 
loaded with 22,000 pages of special-interest provisions. What kind of 
"free trade" is it that provides for U.S. taxpayer subsidies of 
foreign industries and governments?
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
When it comes right down to it, the NAFTA and GATT gang are really 
protectionists. They use the power of government to protect their 
friends. They could care less about protecting American workers, but 
they didn't hesitate to use U.S. taxpayer dollars to protect New York 
investment banks from the consequences of their bad investments in 
Mexico. The GATT treaty was filled with hidden handouts and 
perquisites for the politically powerful, who trumpeted their support 
for "free trade" without publicizing the potential for profit that 
motivated them.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
America's Founding Fathers were all avowed protectionists. To a man, 
they believed that protection of American workers and industries from 
cheap foreign imports is essential to our prosperity, our 
independence, and our sovereignty. The first act passed by our first 
Congress established tariffs on foreign goods -- an essential rite of 
passage in the transformation of our country from dependent colony to 
sovereign nation. Unfortunately, for the last 25 years, U.S. trade 
policy has been dominated by giant corporations that want to take 
advantage of cheap foreign labor and still have open access to 
American markets. Congressmen and executive branch officials 
accommodate these interests with the expectation of future employment 
or other consideration from the companies they favor at the expense of 
their countrymen.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
More and more economists are beginning to recognize that "free trade" 
will bring about the total destruction of the balance between capital 
and labor, allowing capital to squeeze labor costs lower and lower. 
This will drive prices lower too, of course, but lower prices will not 
provide much solace to consumers in the long run, because consumers 
are also workers, and workers without jobs cannot take advantage of 
lower prices.
 <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




