<head>
<title>Duplantier:  MSAs  -- 5/7/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

 May 7, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>MSAs</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
 A march to protest the inequities of managed health care is planned 
for our nation's capital this month. Opposition to the tactics of 
health maintenance organizations is bubbling over.
</i></blockquote>

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Health maintenance organizations (known as HMOs) suffer from a built-
in conflict of interest; the gatekeepers and the CEOs make more money 
when they deny their policyholders the right to see a specialist. 
Congressional Republicans have a good answer to the problem, however -
- one that would put extra money in the pockets of workers whose real 
wages have declined, and ease the strain of downsizing by allowing 
them to take some of their benefits with them when they leave a 
company.
<BR> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The solution is Medical Savings Accounts (known as MSAs), which most 
House Republicans campaigned on in 1994. Congress passed Rep. Bill 
Archer's excellent MSA bill in the Balanced Budget Act, but Clinton 
vetoed the measure. Then the House passed it again in its health care 
reform bill, which is now pending. But President Clinton and the 
Washington press corps are trying to bamboozle the Dole-Gingrich 
Congress into passing the Kennedy-Kassebaum bill without MSAs, in an 
effort to resurrect the Hillary health-care plan resoundingly rejected 
in 1994.
<BR> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Medical Savings Accounts are the best solution to all the problems 
connected with health care: the high cost, the choice of doctors, 
portability, pre-existing conditions, job lock, uninsured Americans, 
gatekeepers, capitation, deductibles, co-payments, paperwork, long-
term care, the looming insolvency of Medicare, and even the decline in 
real wages. Here is how MSAs work: An employer buys his employee a 
high-deductible policy and pre-pays the deductible (up to $2,000 per 
year for singles and $4,000 for families) by putting it each year into 
an individual Medical Savings Account. The employee can use this ready 
cash to visit the doctors, hospitals, and clinics of his choice, and 
the high-deductible policy covers any additional expenses. The 
employee owns his own MSA, and can take it with him when changing 
jobs, thus solving the problems of portability, pre-existing 
conditions, and job lock. MSA funds are available for many medical 
expenses often not covered by company plans or by Medicare. Best of 
all, any MSA funds that an employee does not spend will accumulate in 
his own tax-free, interest-bearing savings account. MSAs thus restore 
consumer discipline to the medical marketplace, providing incentives 
to save.
<BR> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The Archer bill would give MSAs pretty much the same tax-deductibility 
that is now enjoyed exclusively by company-paid plans. Our present 
system unfairly grants tax-deductibility only to plans owned by 
employers, but not to plans that allow individual employees to own 
their own health insurance, control their own health care spending, or 
set up their own plan. The officers of big corporations enjoy gold-
plated health insurance paid for with tax-deductible dollars, but the 
self-employed must buy health insurance with after-tax income. It's 
time for Congress to give us the solution to all these problems: 
Medical Savings Accounts.
 <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




