<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier Slave-Labor Goods -- 5/22/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</B><BR>
<I>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

 May 22, 1996<br></i> 
 <h2>
 SLAVE-LABOR GOODS 
 </h2><blockquote></i><P><I>
Legislators in California and Massachusetts are considering bills to  
prohibit their state governments from buying slave-labor goods. 
 </i></blockquote><P>
Legislation proposed in California requires that all state contracts "shall  
contain a statement in which the contractor attests that no foreign-made  
equipment, materials, or supplies furnished to the state pursuant to the  
contract have been produced in whole or in part by forced labor, convict  
labor, or indentured labor under penal sanction." Legislation proposed in  
Massachusetts would likewise require state contractors to "swear under  
penalty of perjury" that their goods have not been produced by forced  
labor. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 

Carl Olsen of State Department Watch, a nonpartisan foreign policy  
watchdog group, suggests that these proposed bills have been "prompted  
by the Federal government's indifference about slave labor overseas and  
its threat to American workers and firms." While acknowledging that  
"the importation of slave-made goods is banned by federal statute,"  
Olsen argues that "the ban has been easily circumvented by cumbersome  
Customs Service regulations and uncooperative foreign governments.  
The Chinese government," he points out, "has not allowed any  
inspection of its laogai facilities in over a year even though the Customs  
Service has demanded to see numerous ones." Olsen reports that "the  
largest forced labor systems in the world are in China and the former  
Soviet Union. The Chinese laogai factories and farms hold 20 million  
workers, equal in number to the entire workforce of California. Many  
gulags in the former Soviet Union are still in operation." 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 

Neither the Clinton administration nor Congress has shown much  
concern with "slave labor overseas and its unfair economic threat to  
American workers and firms," says Olsen. At a February 29th World  
Affairs Council luncheon in Los Angeles, then-U.S. Trade  
Representative Mickey Kantor "stated that forced labor was not an issue  
in his bilateral negotiations with China. " Olsen notes that Most Favored  
Nation tariff status "was granted to China in 1994 with no human rights  
reservations as in years before," and he predicts that such reservations  
will again fall by the wayside when China's Most Favored Nation status  
comes up for renewal in June. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 

Carl Olsen of State Department Watch says that the State Department's  
1992 Memorandum of Understanding with China regarding the  
inspection of suspected slave-labor facilities "has been ignored by the  
Chinese government without any consequence. The State Department,"  
he adds, "has no regulation to avoid purchasing slave-made goods for its  
own use or for foreign aid programs. It does not intend to insist on anti- 
slave labor policies for multinational organizations such as the United  
Nations and the Organization of American States." Olsen also points out  
that "no agency in the federal government has any contract provision,  
regulation, or monitoring program to prevent the purchase of slave-made  
goods or services. For the billions of dollars of purchases overseas for use  
overseas by the Federal government, there is absolutely no prohibition  
under current law against purchasing and using slave-made goods since  
the goods are not imported into the U.S." 
        
<P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
</body>
</html>

 

