<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier: WELFARE REFORM/MI & MA -- 5/29/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif">
</a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>


<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
May 29, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2> Welfare Reform/MI & MA</h2>


<i><blockquote>


Why does private charity work so much better than public assistance? 
It's because the private benefactor expects to see results from his 
almsgiving. .</blockquote></i>

Private poverty-relief programs emphasize "character-building, one-on-
one mentoring, and a spiritual dimension," says Lawrence Reed of the 
Mackinac Center for Public Policy in Midland, Michigan. Government 
relief programs, on the other hand, generally promote the personal 
imperfections that perpetuate poverty. In the April issue of "Alternatives 
in Philanthropy," published by the Capital Research Center, Reed reports 
that his home state has drastically revamped its welfare program. 
"Michigan abruptly ended the General Assistance program for able-
bodied, childless adults in October 1991 and adopted a 'social contract,' 
whereby welfare recipients are expected to seek work, go to school, or 
perform community service in exchange for benefits," says Reed. "Nearly 
25 percent of Michigan's AFDC recipients are now working. This is 
three times the national average."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Reed thinks the Governor of Michigan is committed to "further reducing 
the role of government and making welfare a largely private initiative." 
He notes that "a growing number of private initiatives to help the poor 
are already underway, some of which sprouted in direct response to the 
state's abolition of General Assistance." Welfare as it currently operates 
"has produced such disastrous consequences that it's hard to imagine 
how a radical overhaul could make things worse," says Larry Reed. "If 
we revitalize the American ideals of charity and self-help, we might end 
up spending less for success than the government now spends for 
failure."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

In the same issue of "Alternatives in Philanthropy," David Tuerck of the 
Beacon Hill Institute in Boston reports that Massachusetts began its own 
welfare overhaul in 1995. "Able-bodied welfare recipients whose 
youngest children have entered school must work at least 20 hours per 
week in a job or community service program," notes Tuerck. "Parents 
under age 18 must live with a responsible adult or in a supervised group 
home. They must stay in school or in a GED program." They receive no 
additional benefits for children born after August 1996.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Though supportive of these reforms, Tuerck insists that the main 
problem with welfare is the way it is funded. "Under the existing system, 
taxpayers send their money to Washington, where most flows into a 
welfare bureaucracy and only a fraction eventually reaches the pockets of 
the poor." Tuerck would retain taxpayer funding of welfare, but make it 
taxpayer-controlled as well. He proposes that "individual taxpayers, both 
itemizers and non-itemizers, receive a 100 percent federal tax credit for 
contributions to eligible charities for up to 25 percent of their federal tax 
liability." David Tuerck argues that such a tax credit would not only 
increase private charitable giving beyond the level of the current public 
dole, but would also guarantee that a far greater percentage of those alms 
actually reach the intended recipients.
<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




